<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Quotas for Russian Oil Tankers Proposed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Quotas for Russian Oil Tankers Proposed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806185194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1459 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806185194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Russian Sea Transport Department might soon 
submit to the government a proposal on the introduction of 
strict quotas on the transportation of Russian oil by Russian 
tankers. 
  A spokesman for the department Dmitriy Kokorin said that at 
the end of last month the leadership of the country's only 
tanker fleet Novoship (Novorossiisk) asked the department and 
the State Oil Company Nafta to give priority to Russian tankers 
in transporting export oil. 
  Novoship and the department account the steady decline in 
the 
share of export cargoes transported by Russian tankers to the 
fact that most oil contracts between Russian exporters and 
foreign customers are on FOB (free on board) terms. 
  Under such contracts exporters deliver oil to the port of 
dispatch while the importer is responsible for the rest of the 
transportation. At the moment most Western oil importers are 
using their own tanker fleets while Novoship tankers are 
standing idle. 
  Novoship has 45 tankers with a combined payload of 2.1 
million tons, 16 oil and ore ships with a payload of 1.4 million 
tons and 5 oil and ore ships working for the Russian-Norwegian 
shipping line Novoklav. 

</TEXT>

