<H3> <TI>   Stage Set for Refugee Return to N. Ossetia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Stage Set for Refugee Return to N. Ossetia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK0906083694 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 8 Jun 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> MK0906083694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report in the "NEGA Reports" column] </F>
  [Text] North Ossetia -- A meeting has taken place in 
Vladikavkaz between republic President Akhsarbek Galazov, 
parliament head Yuriy Biragov, and Provisional Administration 
chief Vladimir Lozovoy. The focus of attention was on matters 
related to the rehabilitation of housing and communications 
destroyed in the course of the tragic events of October and 
November 1992, as well as socioeconomic problems in the state of 
emergency zone. Also taking part in the discussion were members 
of the government and parliament of North Ossetia, as well as 
representatives of federal ministries and departments on a 
fact-finding mission in North Ossetia and Ingushetia. 
  According to Vladimir Lozovoy, a large group of Russian 
Federation ministry and department chiefs arrived in the 
conflict zone to organize preparation for the return of refugees 
and forced resettlers to four populated areas in Prigorodnyy 
Rayon, in line with the Russian Federation president's 30 May 
1994 edict On Introducing a State of Emergency in Parts of the 
Territory of North Ossetia and Ingushetia. The meeting 
pinpointed the main lines of activity by the republic leadership 
toward adjusting the situation. North Ossetia is ready to 
implement the Russian president's edict and a corresponding 
resolution by the Russian Federation Government, but the refugee 
problem should be resolved in a comprehensive manner, on the 
basis of the agreements signed in Kislovodsk. A decisive say 
here belongs to conciliation commissions that were set up in all 
populated areas of Prigorodnyy Rayon. Their activity is already 
yielding some results. Thus, residents in the village of 
Kurtat at their meeting ruled that six Ingushi families return 
to their former homes, specifying them by name. 

</TEXT>

