<H3> <TI>   Experts See `Reconnaissance' Operation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Experts See `Reconnaissance' Operation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK0906084094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 9 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> MK0906084094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Aleksandr Kudakayev report in the "Incident" column: </F>
"Russian Fighter Aircraft Force Landed a U.S. Air Force Plane"] 
  [Excerpt] [Passage omitted] On the evening of 7 June a 
Pentagon spokesman stated that the chain of events connected 
with the U.S. aircraft incident has not been accurately 
recreated yet. U.S. Ambassador to Moscow Thomas Pickering 
thanked the Russian side for "the tact and understanding" shown 
during the plane incident. 
  Some time ago an Israeli private plane was forced to land 
under similar circumstances. Some experts doubt that such 
frequent incidents in the same area are accidental. Rather this 
is a deliberate violation of the established procedures for 
activating the air defense system in this region. Following the 
disintegration of the Union system, Russia had to create new 
border lines, in particular in the Caucasus, which have become a 
subject of study by U.S. and NATO electronic surveillance 
centers in Turkey. The presence of reconnaissance equipment 
aboard the C-130 is not ruled out. According to flight 
documents, there was a diplomatic cargo aboard the plane, and so 
its inspection was unlikely. 

</TEXT>

