<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev Leaves for Caucasus Republics </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Grachev Leaves for Caucasus Republics </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806143294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1329 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806143294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Today Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev left 
for the Caucasian republics on a working visit in order to 
discuss with the Armenian, Azerbaijani, and Georgian leaders 
issues on the establishment of Russian military bases on the 
territory of their countries, Grachev's aide Yelena Agapova told 
INTERFAX. 
  Grachev will first stop in Yerevan and meet Armenian 
President Levon Ter-Petrosyan. Subsequently, Grachev will meet 
Georgian leader Eduard Shevardnadze in Tbilisi. 
  The Azerbaijani leadership has asked Grachev to come to Baku 
in order to speak to Azerbaijani President Geydar Aliyev. 
  Russia intends to have about thirty military bases and 
facilities in neighboring countries, namely, three in Georgia, 
two in Armenia and a station for warning against a military 
attack in Azerbaijan. 
  During his meetings with the Caucasian leaders Grachev is 
expected to discuss peace-keeping operations in Nagorno-Karabakh 
and in the zone of the Georgian-Abkhazian conflict. 
  Well-informed sources in Tbilisi suggested in an interview 
with an INTERFAX correspondent that during Grachev's visit to 
Georgia the peace-keeping operation may begin in the zone of the 
Georgian- Abkhazian conflict. The same sources said that at the 
first stage the conflicting parties would be separated by the 
Russian units stationed in Caucasus. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

