<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev: Meeting on Bosnia Should Be Moved Up </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev: Meeting on Bosnia Should Be Moved Up </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806173194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1537 
GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0806173194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Dmitriy Gorokhov, Nikita </F>
Yermakov, and Igor Shchegolev] 
  [Text] Paris, 8 Jun -- Russia proposes the holding of 
another foreign ministers' meeting on a settlement in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina should be moved up. This was stated today by 
Andrey Kozyrev, head of the Russian foreign policy department, 
speaking to journalists at the Russian Embassy in France. 
  Today's exchange of opinion with French Foreign Minister 
Alain Juppe and other colleagues on the efforts of the "contact 
group" on Bosnia convinces one that the difficulties in its work 
should not serve as pretext for postponing the meeting of 
ministers, he pointed out. On the contrary, "in the next week 
or two" a second meeting of ministers on the Bosnian problem 
should be held. "It is clear that a political level is needed, 
first of ministers, and then also of the leaders of the 
countries in keeping with the initiative of President Boris 
Yeltsin, in order to bring forward a political resolution of the 
conflict," the head of Russian diplomacy stressed. "The `contact 
group' was able to do some important preparatory work, but it 
cannot replace the ministers." So, in his opinion, a ministerial 
meeting should not be postponed. 
  The first such meeting was held in Geneva on 13 May with the 
foreign ministers of Russia, the USA, and five countries of the 
European Union participating. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

