<H3> <TI>   Diplomat Says Geneva Talks on Bosnia `Fruitless' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Diplomat Says Geneva Talks on Bosnia `Fruitless' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806153994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1354 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806153994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature by correspondents </F>
Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy Trubetskoy and others] 
<F P=106> [All quotation marks as received] </F>
  [Text] Moscow hopes that the United States and Russia's 
other western partners will exert their influence on the Bosnian 
Moslems and Croats in order to reach a ceasefire agreement in 
Bosnia and Herzegovina, a top-ranking Russian diplomat in charge 
for the settlement in the former Yugoslavia said in his 
interview with Interfax. 
  In his words, the Geneva meeting between the special envoy 
of 
the UN General Secretary Yasusi Akasi and representatives of the 
confronting Bosnian parties was fruitless. "Moslems and Croats 
agree only to a quadripartite ceasefire with its possible 
prolongation for four weeks. The Bosnian Serbs are ready to 
cease fire at least for four months," the diplomat indicated. 
  As he said, "fears that the Serbs would try to preserve the 
status-quo and to fix themselves on 70 percent of Bosnia and 
Herzegovina stand behind the obstinacy of the Moslems and 
Croats." "One cannot say that these fears are groundless. The 
threat of "an ethnic cleansing" in Bosnia and Herzegovina is 
still preserved and all confronting parties are the source of 
this threat, noted Interfax interlocutor. But it is quite 
obvious that nobody will let the Serbs violate the proportion of 
division which was coordinated at the ministers' meeting in 
Geneva; in accordance with this agreement the Serbs will receive 
49and the Moslem-Croatian federation -- 512000060100f the territory 
of this former Yugoslavian republic." 
  According to the diplomat, "one cannot permit that the fears 
of one of the parties would "suspend" the process of peaceful 
settlement in Bosnia." "In an adverse case the world community 
will be forced to begin everything from the very beginning," he 
said. 

</TEXT>

