<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Seeking To Solve DPRK Nuclear Problem </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Seeking To Solve DPRK Nuclear Problem </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906134994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1220 
GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0906134994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Boris Krivoshey] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 9 Jun (ITAR-TASS) -- Russia is taking steps 
aimed at unblocking the situation around the DPRK by political 
methods. This was stated at a briefing today by Grigoriy 
Karasin, director of the department of information and press of 
the Russian federation Foreign Ministry in connection with the 
recent deterioration of the DPRK's nuclear problem. 
  "This approach," he noted, "envisions the need for Pyongyang 
to ensure the IAEA has access to the relevant facilities and 
information by the agreed deadlines and the convening of an 
International conference for a comprehensive examination of the 
problems of security on the Korean peninsula. If these 
diplomatic efforts are not successful the sanctions proposal 
will have to be examined." 
  Replying to a question regarding relations and economic 
cooperation between Russia and North Korea, Grigoriy Karasin 
said that "relations with the DPRK are developing in a normal 
way, cooperation is continuing, including on the question of the 
work of the lumberjacks on Russian territory." During the talks 
which were held between representatives of the Russian and DPRK 
Foreign Ministries it proved possible to settle a number of 
questions, he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

