<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commentary Opposes Economic Sanctions Against DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commentary Opposes Economic Sanctions Against DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0906020894 Moscow Radio Moscow in Korean 1200 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0906020894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Moscow </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Commentary by (Anatoliy Botakov) from the "Today's World" </F>
program] 
  [Text] The International Atomic Energy Agency's [IAEA] 
letter to UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali is being 
discussed by the UN Security Council. 
  The United States, Japan, and the ROK are vigorously trying 
to impose economic sanctions against Pyongyang. Considering 
that the PRC might veto the decision, the United States is 
evaluating the possibility of so-called sanction measures to 
apply economic pressure. First, the measure bans all contracts 
related to weapon sales. The embargo does not include coal and 
petroleum. The economic sanction measures are another means to 
obtain UN Security Council approval. 
  Russia reminds them of the fact that gradual and phased 
sanctions by an international organ would not be opposed when 
all other measures have failed. Considering the PRC position, I 
think making a decision on an embargo by the UN Security Council 
would be impossible at the moment. 
  Therefore, it is urgent to convene an international 
conference for the security and denuclearization of the Korean 
peninsula as proposed by Russia. The conference may be attended 
by the representatives of the DPRK, South Korea, Russia, the 
United States, the PRC, Japan, the United Nations, and the IAEA. 
The conference should be an authoritative conference that 
contributes to ending the dangerous confrontation on the 
peninsula and enables the DPRK to express its concerns during 
the progress. 
  U.S. President Clinton had a telephone conversation with 
Boris Yeltsin last week and said that the conference may be 
appropriate at a certain time. I would like to ask him what is 
the appropriate time? Is it after sanctions are imposed? I 
doubt anything could be achieved at that point. 
  In addition to its proposal, Moscow is prepared to evaluate 
other coordination measures. However, all possible political 
measures should be taken. 
  There are reports that the United States, Japan, and South 
Korea are preparing three-party sanctions against Pyongyang 
without a UN decision. They should not forget that Russia has 
great economic and trading interests in the DPRK. 
  When independent three-party sanctions are imposed, Russia 
will be in a position to consider its own legal interests. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-39622 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov111_a_94022" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-111 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

