<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Meets Japanese Foreign Ministry Representative </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev Meets Japanese Foreign Ministry Representative </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806214294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1440 
GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0806214294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Andrey Varlamov] </F>
  [Text] Tokyo, 8 Jun -- Russia and Japan have confirmed the 
common policy of the two countries of developing bilateral 
relations and continuing talks on the territorial problem and 
also their readiness to coordinate efforts in the matter of 
settling the crisis situation regarding the DPRK nuclear 
programme. An ITAR-TASS correspondent was informed at the 
Russian department of the Japanese Foreign Ministry that this 
was discussed at a brief meeting between Andrey Kozyrev, the RF 
[Russian Federation] foreign minister, and Nobuo Matsunaga, 
special representative of the Japanese Government to the 
international talks, which were held in Paris today. They are 
taking part in a session of the Organisation of Economic 
Cooperation and Development, which is being held in the French 
capital. 
  The Japanese representative noted that a certain amount of 
progress has been achieved in advancing the political and 
economic dialogue between the two neighbouring countries since 
the visit by Boris Yeltsin, the RF president, to Tokyo and 
stressed the need for the further development of 
Russian-Japanese ties on the basis of the "Tokyo declaration" 
which was signed on the results of the summit in October 1993. 
  The Russian minister confirmed the invitation for Tsutomu 
Hata, the Japanese prime minister, to make an official visit to 
Moscow this year. However, according to the Japanese Foreign 
Ministry staffer, the sides did not touch on the issue of 
specific dates for the possible trip. 

</TEXT>

