<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aviaeksport Chief Denies Blame for PRC TU-154 Crash </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Aviaeksport Chief Denies Blame for PRC TU-154 Crash </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0806124594 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 8 Jun 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM0806124594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS report under the general heading: "Our Aircraft </F>
Are Valued in China, but the Tu-154 Crash Is the Worst in That 
Country's Civil Aviation History"] 
  [Text] Russian spokesmen have categorically denied reports 
from Beijing that the crashed Tu-154 aircraft had supposedly 
undergone two major overhauls before it started operating in the 
PRC. 
  Feliks Myasnikov, general director of the "Aviaeksport" 
Foreign Economic Association, has reported that a new aircaft 
was supplied to China under contract in 1986. Since then the 
airliner, in full accordance with the recommended norms, has 
undergone one planned overhaul, which was carried out at the 
repair plant at Vnukovo in 1992. According to Feliks Myasnikov, 
the Chinese side has not submitted data on the aircraft's 
operation, but there can be no question of its operating life 
having been exceeded with regard to any of the parameters. 
  The Main Aviation Industry Administration of the Russian 
Federation State Committee for Defense Sectors of Industry has 
reported that at the time of the aircraft's handover to the PRC 
it had flown for 32 hours within the framework of control tests. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

