<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Urges Solution To `Nuclear Crisis' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Urges Solution To `Nuclear Crisis' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806192694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1850 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806192694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondents Viktor Demidenko and </F>
Mikhail Melnik] 
  [Text] Kiev 8 June TASS - "If sanctions are imposed on 
North Korea, its leadership will have to act adequately to the 
situation," North Korean Foreign Minister Kim Yong-nam said. 
  Speaking at a news conference in Kiev on Wednesday [8 June], 
Kim Yong-nam said that "we will choose the concrete form of 
self-defence when we know what measures the countries demanding 
`punishment' for North Korea intend to take." 
  The minister stressed that the "nuclear problem is 
artificial. It was created by certain circles in the U.S. and 
IAEA (International Atomic Energy Agency) in order to strangle 
socialism in the country." "The nuclear crisis on the peninsular 
must be solved by the United States and North Korea through 
negotiations," he said. 
  "The participation of other countries is out of the 
question," he added. 
  Commenting on Russia's initiative to convene an 
international 
meeting on North Korea, Kim Yong-nam described it as 
"interesting," adding that "we are studying it." 
  The minister expressed the confidence that "the intention of 
the U.S. and IAEA to inspect nuclear reactors is closely 
connected with the opening up of the country's military 
facilities." He termed it as an "interference in the internal 
affairs of the state." "We are not against inspections, but only 
there where there are nuclear reactors," he added. 
  Speaking about Pyongyang's position, Kim Yong-nam said that 
"until the United States fulfills its obligations in full, North 
Korea will not join the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty." 
"These obligations call for an end to hostile policy and nuclear 
threat to the state, and for preservation of peace and security 
on the peninsular, impartial policy and assistance in converting 
the reactors working on light water," he said. 
  "We are in such a position that we cannot trust the United 
States unless our conditions are met," the minister said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

