<H3> <TI>   Russian-Ukrainian Talks on Black Sea Fleet Continue in Kiev </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian-Ukrainian Talks on Black Sea Fleet Continue in Kiev </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806131794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1308 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806131794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Gondusov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow 8 June TASS -- According to information 
received from Russian naval sources, the main problem of the 
two-day negotiations between the Russian and Ukrainian 
delegations, which began today in Kiev, is to divide the bases 
and coastal infrastructure of the Black Sea Fleet. 
  The Russian delegation is led by roving Ambassador Yuriy 
Dubinin. He arrived in the Ukrainian capital together with 
Admiral Feliks Gromov, commander-in-chief of the Russian Navy. 
The admiral told ITAR-TASS on the eve of the trip, that the 
sides were able to switch over during their talks in Moscow and 
Sevastopol from verbal declarations to the concrete discussion 
of the difficult problem of drawing up a complete list of all 
the warships and other surface craft, and deciding where the 
Black Sea Navy and the Ukrainian naval forces should be based. 
This work will be continued in Kiev. He noted that the 
parameters, according to which the warships should be divided 
between the two sides, were already been determined. Working 
parallel with military experts are economists and financiers, 
who are estimating the cost of the ships and of the fleet's 
infrastructure. Their conclusions will be submitted to the two 
delegations. 
  Gromov believes that both sides will table their own drafts 
during the negotiations. He does not rule out differences on 
individual matters, but believes that it is necessary to do 
everything to achieve mutual understanding. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

