<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Guards Battalion Transferred to Sevastopol From Simferopol </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Guards Battalion Transferred to Sevastopol From Simferopol </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806142194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1358 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806142194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A battalion of 350 Ukrainian guards has been 
transferred to Sevastopol from Simferopol in line with a decree 
issued by President Kravchuk in November of 1991. The National 
Guards Commander in Crimea Aleksandr Kostyukov explained the 
redeployment by the fact that an army compound has become vacant 
for the unit in the outskirts of Sevastopol. The armed guards 
have armored vehicles at their disposal. Their main task, in 
Kostyukov's words is to defend the Ukrainian constitutional 
system, its integrity and frontiers and to maintain public 
order. He stressed that there were no separate assignments for 
the battalion in Sevastopol. 
  Meanwhile, the Coordinating Council of Black Sea Naval 
Officers has sent to the Ukrainian president's ambassador in 
Sevastopol a letter, asking him on what legal grounds the 
battalion was brought into the city and for how long it would 
stay in the port. 
  Kostyukov also reported that there currently is a regiment 
of 
over 1000 guards in Crimea's capital Simferopol. 

</TEXT>

