<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dudayev Says Russian Policy Threatens New Clashes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dudayev Says Russian Policy Threatens New Clashes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806113094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1020 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806113094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The pressure on Chechnya by Russia can seriously 
aggravate the situation in the North Caucasus and result in 
widescale armed clashes, believes Chechen President Dzhokhar 
Dudayev. "The policy pursued by Russia has absolutely no 
prospects and can lead to a global military confrontation 
between Russia and the Caucasus which can finally develop into a 
new Russian-Caucasian war," Dudayev declared in his interview 
with Interfax. 
  As Dudayev asserts, young people from other North Caucasian 
republic who are concerned over the worsening situation around 
Chechnya are coming to Groznyy. In Dudayev's words, they 
express their wish to serve in the armed forces of the Chechen 
republic. 
  Being interviewed by Interfax the day before, Sergey 
Filatov, 
head of the president's administration, accused Dudayev, who has 
repeatedly voiced sharp anti-Russian statements, of actual 
disruption of the negotiating process between Moscow and 
Groznyy. Having recognized that Dudayev possesses the real power 
in Chechnya, Filatov expressed his hope that the Russian-Chechen 
dialogue would be resumed in the near term. 

</TEXT>

