<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Minister on Talks, Nuclear Weapons, Unification </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Minister on Talks, Nuclear Weapons, Unification </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806212594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2103 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806212594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by UKRINFORM correspondent Aleksey Trotsenko for </F>
TASS] 
  [Excerpts] Kiev 9 June TASS -- Ukraine and North Korea 
signed a consular convention and several other inter-state 
agreements on Wednesday [8 June]. 
  North Korean Foreign Minister Kim Yong-nam who is on an 
official visit in Ukraine and his Ukrainian counterpart Anatoliy 
Zlenko also signed a protocol on consultations between the 
Ukrainian and North Korean foreign ministries. 
  After the signing ceremony Kim Yong-nam met with journalists 
to answer their questions. 
  He said that his talks with Ukrainian President Leonid 
Kravchuk, Deputy Parliamentary Chairman Aleksandr Tkachenko and 
Foreign Minister Zlenko helped him understand better the 
processes going on in Ukraine. 
  Speaking about the nuclear problem, the minister stressed 
that it is "artificial. It was created by certain circles in 
the U.S. and IAEA (International Atomic Energy Agency) in order 
to strangle socialism in the country." "The nuclear crisis on 
the peninsular must be solved by the United States and North 
Korea through negotiations," he said. [passage omitted] 
  He emphasised that the peaceful settlement of the conflict 
will largely depend on the successful outcome of the talks with 
the United Nations and IAEA. He expressed regret that the first 
two rounds of talks did not bring the desired results and noted 
that North Korea pins hopes on the third round. [passage omitted] 
  Asked about what nuclear weapons North Korea could afford 
today, Kim Yong-nam replied that "we have no any nuclear 
weapons. Moreover, we have neither possibilities, nor equipment, 
nor funds to make them." 
  Speaking about prospects for reunification with South Korea, 
the minister said that only peaceful reunification is possible, 
without interference of other countries. The two countries 
should form a confederation, while preserving their systems and 
governments, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

