<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karasin: Bosnia Peace Efforts Need Acceleration </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karasin: Bosnia Peace Efforts Need Acceleration </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906173894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1628 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0906173894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Boris Krivoshey] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 9 TASS -- Process of peaceful settlement 
in the former Yugoslavia is nowadays in need of urgent 
activization, Grigoriy Karasin, spokesman for the Russian 
Foreign Ministry, told a Moscow briefing on Thursday. 
  Though "the Contact Group", which communicates with the 
belligerents directly, has made an important preparatory 
contribution, it is still unable to supplant a meeting of 
foreign ministers, he said. 
  "Moscow considers it necessary to accelerate preparations 
for 
holding a new meeting of foreign ministers. We believe the 
meeting could take place within a week or two," the spokesman 
said. 
  Moscow hails the fact that the warring parties in Bosnia 
have 
agreed through the mediation of the United Nations to suspend 
offensive operations and other provocative acts for a month, he 
said. The agreement comes into force tomorrow at noon (local 
time). 
  "The most important thing at present is the fact that the 
parties involved in the military conflict in former Yugoslavia 
are actually prepared to carry out the reached agreement. The 
vitality of the truce depends on their position, self-restraint 
and political will," Karasin added. 
  Aleksandr Belyayev, a Russian soldier of the UN Protection 
Force, who was fatally wounded in the beginning of this months, 
died on June 7. A close investigation into the tragic accident 
is now under way, Karasin told the briefing. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

