<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow Visit Postponed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moscow Visit Postponed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906202894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1857 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0906202894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, May 9 (TANJUG) -- President of the Bosnian 
Serb Republic (R.S.) Radovan Karadzic's visit to Moscow has been 
postponed probably until early next week, as he has not received 
the necessary travel papers from the U.N. sanctions committee, 
TANJUG learned here on Thursday. 
  The U.N. Security Council imposed in late May 1992 the 
comprehensive and mandatory sanctions on the Federal Republic of 
Yugoslavia (Serbia/Montenegro) for its alleged involvement in 
the civil war in neighbouring Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Grigoriy Karasin, senior official of the Russian Foreign 
Ministry, said on Thursday that Karadzic's visit to Moscow would 
be private, but he did not rule out the possibility of the R.S. 
president's meeting with officials. He is coming to Moscow to 
receive the `Mikhail Sholokhov' award for literature, but the 
posssibility is not ruled out that he might meet with some 
officials. This will depend also on the schedule of the 
officials with whom Karadzic wants to hold talks, said Karasin. 
  In Moscow, Karadzic is to receive the award which was 
conferred on him by the Russian Writers' Association in 
acknowledgment of his literary work. The `Mikhail Sholokhov' 
award was instituted two years ago at the initiative of the 
Russian Writers' Association and the Russian writers' STMCK 
Company. 
  Karadzic is the first foreigner to receive the award which 
has so far gone to six Russian writers. 

</TEXT>

