<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Military Cooperation Talks Continue With Malaysia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Military Cooperation Talks Continue With Malaysia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906171694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1536 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0906171694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia and Malaysia intend to continue their talks 
on military cooperation, Interfax was informed by Sergey 
Chumachenko, head of the Rosvooruzheniye state company's foreign 
economic relations department, told Interfax. The company 
signed a contract worth 600 million US dollars on June 7 for the 
supply of 18 MiG-29 fighter planes to Malaysia. 
  Chumachenko said that the two countries would, "after a 
short 
breather," continue talks on a broad range of issues, which 
could include upgrading Malaysia's navy. 
  He denied that Moscow had sold the fighters on the cheap. He 
said representatives from the Dementiyev Aviation and Industrial 
Association, which manufactures the aircraft, had been present 
at the talks and when the contract was signed and they would 
hardly have agreed to under-price their own products. 
  The contract with Malaysia also provides for the supply of 
facilities to service the aircraft before the end of the year, 
training for staff, and spare parts both during and after the 
guarantee period runs out. Approximately 75 pct of the total 
cost of the contract will be paid off in hard currency, and the 
remainder in supplies of palm-oil for sale by Moscow to other 
countries. 
  Rosvooruzhheniye, Russia's leading exporter and importer of 
arms and military hardware, was set up at the end of last year 
after a decree by Russian President Boris Yeltsin. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

