<H3> <TI>   Indonesia Tries To Resolve DPRK Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Indonesia Tries To Resolve DPRK Nuclear Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1006014194 Moscow Radio Moscow in Korean 1000 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1006014194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Moscow </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Indonesian Foreign Ministry's Public Affairs 
Director (Abid) said in an interview with ITAR-TASS on 9 June 
that, as the chair state of the nonaligned movement, Indonesia 
is making quiet diplomatic efforts to peacefully resolve the 
serious nuclear issue of the Korean peninsula. Indonesia is 
relying on the dispatch of special envoys to countries directly 
concerned of the dispute, including the DPRK, the United States, 
the PRC, and Japan, and the contact with the International 
Atomic Energy Agency in Vienna. These are aimed at peacefully 
solving all the problems, he said. 
  The Foreign Ministry spokesman pointed out that the nuclear 
issue of the Korean peninsula had been discussed in depth during 
the meeting of the foreign ministers of nonaligned countries 
held in Cairo some time ago. The participants agreed that 
problems concerning the Korean peninsula should be solved 
through peaceful means and that contacts between all parties 
concerned should continue. 

</TEXT>

