<DOCNO> FBIS4-39694 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov112_a_94017" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-112 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   ASEAN Interested in Russian Military Equipment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ASEAN Interested in Russian Military Equipment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906122494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1039 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0906122494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russian First Vice Premier Oleg Soskovets commented 
on the details of the contract for selling 18 Russian MiG-29 
jets to Malaysia. He said that the contract costing 550 million 
dollars will ensure employment for 100,000 people on Russian 
industrial military enterprises over the next two years. There 
will also be more jobs at enterprises producing spare parts for 
military jets until the contract expires. 
  Soskovets emphasized that other ASEAN (Association of South 
East Asian Nations) countries had also showed interest in 
Russian military equipment. Soskovets stressed that the 
contract with Malaysia was even more important since in 1994 the 
Russian Air Forces had ordered only 17 military jets from the 
military industrial enterprises. 
  Speaking on the contacts with Russian diplomats in Kuala 
Lumpur and Delhi where the Russian governmental delegation had 
stopped on its way from Malaysia, Soskovets regretted that 
Russian diplomats hardly knew the realities of life in Russia or 
bilateral economic relations and just kept complaining about the 
conditions of living and working in the country where they were 
sent. Soskovets announced that he had asked Deputy Foreign 
Minister Igor Ivanov to make a report on the performance of the 
Russian embassies in India and Malaysia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

