<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dniester Leadership Complains Over Stalled Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dniester Leadership Complains Over Stalled Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906162794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1446 
GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0906162794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Demidetskiy] </F>
  [Text] Kishinev, 9 Jun -- The Dniester Republic leaders 
have accused the Moldovan leadership of dragging out the talks 
on a settlement to the Dniester region issue, said a statement 
issued today in Tiraspol by the Dniester Republic president's 
and government's press service. The document claims that "the 
attempts made by Tiraspol to speed up the negotiation process, 
which was started with Russia's mediation, has again run into a 
silent blockade by Moldova, and President Mircea Snegur has in 
fact withdrawn from further talks." 
  In this regard Igor Smirnov, head of the Dniester Republic, 
has appealed to Ambassador Vladlen Vasev, plenipotentiary envoy 
of the Russian president, to exert all his influence on Mircea 
Snegur. The statement also underlines that the inhabitants of 
the left bank of the Dniester river have postively assessed the 
joint statement by the leaders of Moldova and the Dniester 
Republic on finding a settlement to the aftermath of the armed 
conflict, which was signed at the end of April. 
  At a time when President Igor Smirnov is complaining about 
the lack of progress at the talks, State Secretary Valeriy 
Litskiy, chief coordinator at the talks from the Tiraspol side, 
discussed today with the CSCE mission in Moldova prospects of 
resuming the dialogue. They agreed that the talks could be 
continued in the near future following the return to Kishinev of 
Richard Samuel, head of the CSCE mission. The arrival of 
Vladlen Vasev, the special Russian envoy, is also expected then. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

