<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Indian Minister Satisfied With Visit Results </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Indian Minister Satisfied With Visit Results </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906142294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1327 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0906142294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Boris Mainayev] </F>
  [Text] Bishkek 9 June TASS -- Indian Minister of State for 
External Affairs Salman Khurshid expressed satisfaction with the 
results of his working visit to Kirghizia [Kyrgyzstan]. 
  The minister said that all agreements, which are to be 
signed 
during Indian Prime Minister P.V. Narasimha Rao's forthcoming 
official visit to Kirghizia, are almost ready or in the final 
stage of completion. The Indian premier is scheduled to visit 
the Republic in the first half of July. The agreements will 
cover a wide range of bilateral relations between the two 
countries, from trade, economic, cultural ties to working out 
fast coordinated actions in fight against international 
terrorism and drug trafficking. 
  A group of Indian businessmen, who are accompanying the 
minister, finalized their priorities in cooperation with their 
Kirghiz counterparts. The Indians are interested in the 
possibility of setting up joint enterprises to produce medicine, 
process agricultural produce, dress leather, manufacture paper, 
extract minerals and create infra-structure and 
telecommunications networks. 
  Salman Khurshid said that the two sides have almost agreed 
to 
allot a supply quota of mercury, antimony, rare-earth metals and 
dressed leather and pelts to India. According to the minister, 
India intends to review the agreement's clauses about making 
investments in Kirghizia and crediting specific branches of its 
economy. This is being done to find a compromise and satisfy 
both parties, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

