<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Base Issue Settled `in Principle' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Base Issue Settled `in Principle' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906194194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1556 
GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0906194194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Mikhail Shevtsov] </F>
  [Text] Yerevan, 9 Jun -- The issue of the Russian base in 
Armenia has been settled in principle. It is planned to have 
one efficient military base installed in two localities on the 
Republic's territory. The main installation is to be in the 
Gyumri locality, where a Russian motorized infantry division is 
currently quartered, while part of the base's subunits will be 
stationed in Yerevan, where a Russian motorized infantry 
regiment is based at present. This opinion was shared by the 
members of the Russian military delegation at the summing-up 
conference held today by Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev. 
He noted that Armenian President Levon Ter-Petrosyan was 
sympathetic toward the proposed Russian military base. 
  According to Grachev, the bases in Armenia should be set up 
by 1 August 1994. The minister noted that it will be quite a 
powerful body of troops and that there are plans to include 
antiaircraft and air force -- with the exception of 
long-distance aircraft -- elements alongside ground troops. "It 
will be a powerful air mobile force," Pavel Grachev said, "which 
can be deployed in any danger area at short notice should the 
need arise." 
  Apart from this, the question of creating a joint 
Russian-Armenian antiaircraft defense system within the 
framework of the collective security treaty was also discussed. 
The extent of the Russian and Armenian contributions in terms 
of materiel and personnel was established. In particular, 
Russia plans to station additional air defense subunits in 
Armenia to cover certain sections and control the Armenian 
airspace. These will be missile complexes and a squadron of 
interceptor planes. The final decision on the whole complex of 
questions concerning the Russian military base in Armenia will 
be made at the presidential level. 
  As one of the participants in the talks said to an ITAR-TASS 
correspondent, Russia intends to take legal posession of its 
military base for the period of 25 years. At the same time the 
Russian side hopes that "conditions do not mean that the base is 
being rented." Besides, the Russian side proposed that Moscow 
exercise direct control over the base. 
  According to Pavel Grachev, the Armenian side promised to 
assist in funding and provision for the Russian military base. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

