<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Speaker To Run for Premiership </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Parliament Speaker To Run for Premiership </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906165194 Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network in Estonian 1500 
GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0906165194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network </F>
<F P=105>  Estonian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Riigikogu Speaker Ulo Nugis made a statement at a 
news conference today, and said that he is ready to run for 
premier. The Riigikogu speaker acknowledged that the present 
crisis within the Fatherland party has transported itself to the 
Cabinet, and that there is a serious danger that this may turn 
into a constitutional crisis. Now some of his fellow thinkers 
in the republican group within the Fatherland Party have 
recommended that he should stand for the Fatherland's chairman 
and take it upon himself to form a new government, as a 
candidate for premier. According to Nugis, he sees this as a 
task from his fellow thinkers. Shirking one's responsibility 
can only be seen as a betrayal of one's ideals, said Nugis. 
  According to him, the Riigikogu has now formed the opinion 
that the Government led by Mart Laar cannot stay. In the 
opinion of the Riigikogu speaker, parliament is ready for a vote 
of no confidence in the present government, regardless of the 
outcome of the elections at the Fatherland meeting. According 
to Nugis, the government coalition is also of the same opinion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-39726 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov112_t_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-112 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Says No Place for Laar in Government </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Says No Place for Laar in Government </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS1006094094 Tallinn BNS in English 1805 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1006094094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, June 09, BNS -- Estonian parliament 
Chairman Ulo Nugis, who today announced his readiness to take 
over as new head of the government, also said he would not keep 
for current Prime Minister Mart Laar a post in his cabinet. 
  "I don't consider it possible that Mart Laar would be a 
minister in my government," Nugis said. 
  But, he said, adding a mellow tone, Mart Laar is a young man 
for whom the heights of life are still ahead. "I still think 
that when the current government is replaced, Laar will not be 
lost for Estonia as a politician," Nugis said. He mentioned 
that a place for Laar could be found in one of the country's 
future governments. 
  The parliament chairman said that if the president now 
proposes to him to set up a new Cabinet, it is possible that he 
will include the rest of the current ministers in his Cabinet 
list. 
  "To become a prime minister is not my ultimate goal, but it 
is a means with which I wish to resolve the government crisis 
that has energed in Estonia and avoid splitting of Pro Patria," 
Nugis said at a press conference today. 
  "Fellow members from the Republican faction of Pro Patria 
have made a proposal to me to stand as candidate for the post of 
Pro Patria chairman and, as a prime minister candidate, take 
upon myself the formation of a new government," Nugis said in 
his personal written statement released today. "Let my personal 
feelings be left aside at this point, but I take the proposal 
made by the Republicans as a task from persons with whom I share 
views," he said, adding that shirking responsibility could only 
be interpreted as an act of treachery to his ideals. 
  Nugis said a notion had emerged in the parliament that a 
government under Mart Laar cannot continue in power. In his 
words the parliament is ready to fail the current government in 
a confidence vote regardless of the outcome of the Pro Patria 
congress. He said this was also the position of the governing 
coalition. When asked how he could be so sure about this, Nugis 
said that he as the speaker of the parliament knows well his 
fellow MP's. 
  Article 97 of the Estonian Constitution gives the president 
the right to call a new general election at the government's 
proposal within three days after a vote of no-confidence in the 
government or the prime minister. Observers say it is in 
Nugis' interests that no such proposal would come from the 
current government, as this would add uncertainty to his 
prospects of becoming prime minister. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

