<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Head of State Apparatus To Be Cut by One-Third </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Head of State Apparatus To Be Cut by One-Third </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK0906123494 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 9 Jun 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> MK0906123494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed NEGA report in the "Georgia" column] </F>
  [Text] Eduard Shevardnadze has signed a special edict 
whereby within the next few days a reorganization in the 
Georgian head of state's apparatus is to begin. On 8 June, 
Chief of Staff Vazha Lordkipanidze told a news conference that 
the number of apparatus staff will be cut by one-third, with all 
the subdivisions moving over to a contract system. At present 
approximately 130 people work in the apparatus. Cadre selection 
is done in accordance with two main criteria: high 
professionalism and moral integrity, regardless of affiliation 
with any political party or public movement. Lordkipanidze 
denied allegations by a number of parliamentarians that the 
apparatus' hard currency spending for foreign trips is double 
that of analogous parliament bills. "In accordance with a 
memorandum by the Georgian Finance Ministry," he said, "in 1994 
the apparatus spent $11,000 for these purposes, while parliament 
spent $12,600." The Georgian head of state's chief of staff 
also stated that contrary to some perceptions, the apparatus has 
never been bloated but corresponded to international standards 
and proportions. Moreover, Lordkipanidze said the presidential 
apparatuses in countries the same size as Georgia number on 
average up to 500 officers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

