<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Filatov: Russia Not Threatened With Disintegration </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Filatov: Russia Not Threatened With Disintegration </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1006074194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 2245 
GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1006074194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 10 Jun -- "Russia is not threatened with the 
fate of the USSR, which disintegrated. The fourth anniversary 
since the day that the declaration on the state sovereignty of 
the Russian Federation was adopted on 12 June, 1990, confirms 
that the Russian Federation, in acquiring its independence, has 
been preserved as an integral state and is continuing to grow 
stronger." This was the stand expressed by Sergey Filatov, head 
of the Russian President's administration, on the eve of the 
state holiday. 
  Filatov attributes great significance in the strengthening 
of 
the Federation to the working out of a new regional policy, 
which still has not been reinforced by the constitutions of the 
Russian republics, by the regulations of the krays and oblasts, 
and by the law on local administration, which the State Duma is 
scheduled to adopt in June. According to Filatov, the efforts 
of the state legal administration and the directorate for work 
with the territories under the Russian president, as well as of 
the Ministry for Nationalities and Regional Policy Affairs, will 
be aimed at equipping the subjects of the Federation with their 
own legislation. 
  In Filatov's opinion, adopting the bilateral treaty between 
Russia and Tatarstan -- a document that became the prologue to 
establishing new relations between the center and the subjects 
of the Federation -- was an important landmark in strengthening 
the Russian Federation. Similar agreements will be signed in 
the near future with Kabardino-Balkaria, Bashkortostan, and 
Kaliningrad Oblast, and in the future with all subjects of the 
Federation. 
  Filatov said that it was the purpose of state policy to 
achieve a "wealthy and uniform standard of living for all the 
citizens of Russia," which is only attainable in conditions 
where there is accord in society. 
  To implement the treaty on public accord, to which 854 
state, 
political, and public figures put their signatures to last 
month, a decree from Boris Yeltsin on the transformation of the 
public chamber supervised by the Russian president into a 
conciliatory coordinating body is expected in the near future. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

