Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Intelligence Official on Wide Range of Threats </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Intelligence Official on Wide Range of Threats </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906115294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1111 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0906115294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Olga Semenova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 9 TASS -- All kinds of inventions 
concerning "the decisive contribution of nuclear spies, 
including agents from among Western nuclear scientists, to the 
development of nuclear weapons in this country are, to put it 
mildly, at variance with the historical truth," according to 
deputy director of the Russian external intelligence service 
Colonel-General Vyacheslav Trubnikov. 
  Trubnikov said in an exclusive interview with ITAR-TASS 
about 
the place of the intelligence service in ensuring Russia's state 
sovereignty and its role in a democratic state that "the 
development of nuclear weapons in our country was a result of 
the efforts of our scientists, such as Kurchatov, Khariton, 
Zeldovich, and many others. The atom bomb is not a simple device 
that could be seen in one place and then copied at home. If our 
science had not come up close to the understanding of the secret 
of the atomic nucleus, it would have been simply unable to 
understand and evaluate the information gleaned by our 
intelligence in the nuclear field". 
  "It is now history, and when history is recorded mistakes 
are 
often made due to deliberate omissions of some things or 
deliberate highlighting of other things. The intelligence 
service does not claim other people's achievements. It has 
enough of its own. The achievement of the intelligence service 
in this case consisted in sensing in good time the important 
trend in the development of science and technology which had a 
colossal military potential and succeeded in obtaining 
information which enabled us to accelerate -- I repeat, 
accelerate -- work in the development of nuclear weapons in our 
country," Trubnikov said. 
  He said the external intelligence service is playing a 
considerable role in ensuring Russia's security, although this 
role is not always made visible. He stressed that "on the whole 
the trends in the global development are favourable for our 
country, but the spectrum of threats remains quite extensive". 
  The general said that the Russian intelligence service can 
compete quite effectively with the recognised leaders of world 
espionage as the CIA, Mossad, and the British secret service. 
"We have always been in the same league and, I want to believe, 
will remain in it always," he said. 
  General Trubnikov added that "should the personnel of our 
competitor services find themselves in conditions similar to 
those in which the Russian intelligence service is finding 
itself now, few would be able to stand it. As regards our 
people, they are serving and will continue to do so". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-39747 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov112_b_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-112 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   FIS Official Discounts `Nuclear Spying' Report </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    FIS Official Discounts `Nuclear Spying' Report </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK1006084594 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 10 Jun 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> MK1006084594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS report under the "Special Services" rubric: </F>
"Russian Intelligence Service in Top League"] 
  [Text] All sorts of conjectures about the decisive 
contribution made by "nuclear spies" -- which include "agents" 
from among Western nuclear scientists -- to the creation in our 
country of nuclear weapons do not correspond with the historical 
truth. This was stated by Colonel General Vyacheslav Trubnikov, 
first deputy director of the Russian Foreign Intelligence 
Service [FIS]. 
  "In reality the creation of nuclear weapons in our country 
came as a result of the efforts of our science, of such 
outstanding representatives of which as Kurchatov, Khariton, 
Zeldovich, and many others. The atomic bomb is no simple device 
you can steal a look at somewhere and then copy it back home. 
Had not our science come close to unraveling the secrets of the 
nucleus, it would simply not have been able to understand and 
appreciate the information on the range of nuclear problems that 
our intelligence service was obtaining," the general underlined. 
  Vyacheslav Trubnikov pointed out that the role of the 
Foreign 
Intelligence Service in assuring Russia's security is very 
appreciable although it is not always in the public eye. He 
also thinks that "the tendencies of world development are on the 
whole favorable for our country, while the spectrum of threats 
still remains rather broad." In his words, the Russian 
intelligence service stands up well to "competition" from such 
recognized leaders of world spying as the U.S. CIA, the Israeli 
Mosad, and the secret service of Great Britain: "We have always 
been in this league and, one would like to believe, will always 
remain in it." There he stressed: "Were the personnel of our 
"competition" in the sort of conditions the Russian intelligence 
service is at the moment, few would stand up to them. Ours 
carry on serving and will serve!" 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

