<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Discusses Fall in Industrial Output </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Discusses Fall in Industrial Output </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906165094 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1400 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0906165094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Chernyshova, with recorded comments </F>
by O. Soskovets, first deputy chairman of the Russian Council of 
Ministers, from the 9 June government session; from the 
"Novosti" newscast] 
  [Excerpts] [Chernyshova] Russian enterprises' output 
between January and May this year was depressingly low. 
Production in real terms declined in comparison with the same 
period last year by 26 percent. One can only wonder what was 
then the general decline in production for the whole period of 
reforms, for example, since 1991. 
  [Soskovets] In some enterprises production fell by up to 80 
percent, in some by 50 percent. 
  [Chernyshova] Out of 406 of the most important categories of 
products only 20 types have shown some progress. Production of 
the rest, which make up the other 94 percent, is badly declining 
by more than a third. The machine-building industry is the 
worst hit. Production here declined by 45 percent. Many 
enterprises stand still and their number increases every month. 
In May there were 5,500. 
  [Passage omitted: Some of the problems are explained by the 
seeming unwillingness of the Russian manufacturers to improve 
their products so as to successfully compete with imported goods] 
  [Soskovets] The positive discrimination against the imported 
machines does not make sense. We have somehow overlooked this 
important aspect of industrial relations during our reforms -- 
that is, discipline -- not only at the enterprises and in 
industry but in the government as well. I think the work should 
begin here. 

</TEXT>

