<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Soskovets: Industry in `Crisis' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Soskovets: Industry in `Crisis' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906171494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1536 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0906171494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] First Vice Prime Minister Oleg Soskovets believes 
that the word "crisis" should be prevalent while describing the 
current situation in Russian industry. He made this statement 
at a government meeting in Moscow Thursday. 
  Soskovets harshly criticized the leaders of some federal 
ministries and agencies, including the Machine-Building 
Committee and the Atomic Energy Ministry, for poor discipline 
and feeble control over the situation in specific branches. 
Commenting on the performance of a number of federal executive 
bodies, he said "We are doing our job very badly." 
  Soskovets said the government meeting had summed up the 
results of its performance in the first half of the year. "There 
are no outstanding success in the sphere of industrial 
production, an unbiased assessment is needed," he said, adding 
"the movement of reforms will depend on how we use the executive 
power we are entrusted with." 
  Soskovets said Russia had lost its positions on the world 
arms market. Soviet arms exports totalled 30 percent of the 
world market compared to the USA's 35 percent. 
  Now the situation has thoroughly changed, he said. Russia's 
exports amount for a mere five percent, while the U.S.A. 
controls 65 percent of the world arms market. "We have suffered 
great losses in this area, it is necessary to restore our 
positions gradually, step by step," Soskovets said. 

</TEXT>

