<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bill on Supporting Small Businesses Approved </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bill on Supporting Small Businesses Approved </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906135094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1256 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0906135094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Oleg Velichko] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 9 TASS -- The bill "on the state support 
of small businesses in the Russian Federation," which was 
discussed by the Russian Government today ahead of its 
consideration in the parliament, is designed to give more 
freedom to the Russian people in the use of their 
entrepreneurial abilities. This was said by Chairman of the 
Russian Anti-Monopoly Committee Leonid Bochin during the 
government meeting on Wednesday. 
  The number of employees of a small business in the industry 
and construction was fixed at 200 people, in agriculture and 
other branches of production, wholesale trading, science and 
scientific services at 50, and in retail trading and the 
non-production sphere at 15. 
  Natural persons engaged in entrepreneurial activity without 
obtaining the status of a legal person are also regarded as 
small businesses. 
  Leonid Bochin said the state support of small businesses 
will 
take the form of a simplified procedure for registering and 
licencing their activity, support for their foreign economic 
activity, the organisation of training and retraining, as well 
as the provision of easy access to financial, material, 
technical and information resources. 
  The new law stipulates that no state support will be 
extended 
to small businesses in which one or several legal persons hold 
shares of the authorised capital in excess of 25 percent. 
Annually at least 0.5 percent of the total spending from the 
federal, regional and local budgets will be alloted to support 
small businesses. Taxes will be levied on small businesses in 
the five first years of their activity, but some tax breaks are 
envisioned. 
  The government approved the bill on the whole and decided to 
send it to the State Duma after putting final touches to it, 
taking into account critical remarks and proposals made during 
the discussion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

