<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Signs Edicts on Housing, Construction </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Signs Edicts on Housing, Construction </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1006115294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1040 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1006115294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In Friday's opening address to a national conference 
on housing policies under free-market relations Russia's First 
Vice Premier Oleg Soskovets said that in a bid to stabilize the 
sphere of housing construction with the help of private 
investment, President Yeltsin has signed a packet of new 
decrees. The conference opened in the State Palace of the 
Moscow Kremlin. President Yeltsin is attending its sittings. 
  Soskovets said Yeltsin signed a decree on housing loans, a 
decree on construction certificates and a decree on the sale of, 
and commercial investment in, unfinished construction projects. 
  According to Soskovets, the national budget revenue in the 
first five months of 1994 fell 5.2 trillion rubles short of its 
target. He felt economic recovery depended, in great measure, on 
investment in housing construction. He said the government must 
offer private entrepreneurs reliable, including state, 
guarantees for investment in that field. 
  A second packet of legislation on more economic reform is in 
the making and legal moves are being made to reduce, as of 1996, 
basic, including profit and value added, taxes by 10 to 20 
percent, Soskovets said. The government, he said, also intends 
to hold tenders among those wishing to sell products to the 
state and intends to sell part of unfinished construction 
projects to private entrepreneurs in a bid to lure more private 
investment into the industry. 

</TEXT>

