<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Possible Tripling in Produce Prices Feared </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Possible Tripling in Produce Prices Feared </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK0906124694 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 9 Jun 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> MK0906124694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Agricultural Products Purchase </F>
Prices May Rise"] 
  [Text] Purchase prices for 1994 agricultural produce in 
the Russian Federation may almost triple, Ministry of 
Agriculture price policy board experts believe. Calculated on 
the basis of current market prices and on the expected level of 
inflation, purchase prices will amount to: about 220,000 rubles 
[R] per one tonne of wheat; R350,000 per one tonne of sunflower; 
R70,000 per one tonne of sugar beet; and R200,000 per one tonne 
of potatoes. According to the experts' count, these prices will 
ensure profitability of wheat and sunflower (121 and 125 percent 
correspondingly). Potatoes (with profitability at 24 percent) 
and sugar beet (at 8 percent) are proving to be unprofitable. 
The document underlines that prices of agricultural produce 
will be determined by those who sell and buy it, and their 
regulation by state organs is not permitted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

