<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Upper House's Shirshov Wants R55 Trillion for Army </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Upper House's Shirshov Wants R55 Trillion for Army </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0906161594 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 9 Jun 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM0906161594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Petr Karapetyan report: "The Federation Council Will Be </F>
Consistent and It Will Not Let the Figure 37 Slip Through -- 
This Was Declared at a Meeting With Journalists by Federation 
Council Security and Defense Committee Chairman Petr Shirshov"] 
  [Text] With the expenditure level of 37.126 trillion 
rubles [R] stipulated by the draft budget, Shirshov said, the 
systematic process of replacing obsolescent and worn out combat 
and technical resources will, in practice, grind to a halt, 
while training (studies and drill) will be cut. This, in turn, 
will make it impossible to ensure that the combat readiness and 
manageability of the Armed Forces will be maintained at the 
requisite level. The training of someone in handling an assault 
rifle alone, according to Shirshov's calculations, sets the 
state back some R130,000, while that of tank gun operators 
requires some R7 million, and company level tactical exercises 
"cost" R137 million. 
  Apart from anything else, increasing the defense budget to 
R55 trillion will open the way for the budgets of the 33 
Federation components to be topped up significantly. To 
compare: The amounts expounded in the draft Federal budget, the 
committee chairman noted, allow for six or seven federation 
components to "make a living." For instance, one 
military-industrial complex enterprise "supports" a region's 
population 5-10 times bigger than the number of workers at the 
enterprise. Up to 30 percent of the cost of military hardware 
and arms for the Russian Army constitutes expenditure by 
enterprises on the social sphere. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-39768 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov112_c_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-112 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Committee Head: Military Budget Insufficient </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Committee Head: Military Budget Insufficient </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906172794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1536 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0906172794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Federation Council, the upper house of the 
Russian parliament, will find it extremely difficult to approve 
the federal 1994 budget as it was passed by the State Duma, the 
lower house, in second reading Wednesday, Budget Committee 
Chairman Nikolay Gonchar told journalists. 
  In particular, he described the increase of the military 
expenses by 3.5 trillion rubles rather than by 18 trillion as 
proposed by the Federation Council as insufficient. This 
decision, he said, will bring the manufacturing industries of 
Russia's 33 regions to their knees. 
  Gonchar was critical of the Duma decision to set up an 
extra-budgetary army support fund where finances obtained from 
privatization would be channeled. He said that if cash were 
available, it had to be included in the budget. 
  He also thought that the financing of regions was 
insufficient. 
  Gonchar thought that the upper house could not confine its 
functions to approval or disapproval of what the Duma decided 
about the budget. He did not rule out the possibility that 
conciliation procedures could be used to have the budget 
endorsed by the upper house. 

</TEXT>

