<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vice Premier Landyk for Economic Unity of CIS, E. Europe </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Vice Premier Landyk for Economic Unity of CIS, E. Europe </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906183894 Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service in Ukrainian 
1500 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0906183894 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  The former USSR countries and the East European states -- 
Poland, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, and Hungary -- should 
unite economically with the aim of protecting their markets. 
Ukraine's Deputy Premier Valentyn Landyk said this in an 
interview for the mass media. He pointed out that the West 
European markets are not waiting for Ukrainian products, but at 
the same time everything possible is being done by Western firms 
to conquer the CIS markets. In the opinion of Valentyn Landyk, 
Ukraine's export potential today is not as high as one would 
like it to be -- mainly raw materials are offered for export. 
Our state can sell its industrial products to Russia and other 
Commonwealth countries. 
  The Ukrainian deputy prime minister emphasized that our 
state's accession to the CIS Economic Union with the rights of 
an associate member is an important move. An associate member 
is even in a better situation as it has more freedom and elbow 
room, underlined Valentyn Landyk. 

</TEXT>

