<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Grachev Talks With Armenian Leaders </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Grachev Talks With Armenian Leaders </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906112994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1021 
GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0906112994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS special correspondents Tigran Liloyan </F>
and Mikhail Shevtsov] 
  [Text] Yerevan, 9 Jun -- Siting of Russian military bases 
in Armenia, service by Armenian lads in Russian units stationed 
on the state's territory, and also conditions of bringing 
peacemaking forces into the region -- these questions are at the 
center of attention at talks Russian Defense Minister Pavel 
Grachev has been having today with the Republic's leaders. He 
is making a working trip round the Transcaucasus. 
  As you know, at a meeting of military department heads of 
Armenia, Azerbaijan, and Nagorno-Karabakh with the mediation of 
Pavel Grachev, a protocol was drafted on the first stage of a 
settlement -- cease-fire and disengagement of the sides. By the 
end of May, it was planned to introduce about 1,800 Russian 
peacemakers into the conflict zone, but the protocol was not 
signed by the Azeri side, which insisted that practically 
simultaneously with the disengagement of the forces Armenia 
should start freeing the Azeri territories it seized in the 
course of the conflict. This is the problem Pavel Grachev has 
to discuss at his coming meeting on 11 June in Baku with 
Azeribaijani President Heydar Aliyev. 

</TEXT>

