<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Foreign Minister on Conditions for IAEA Inspections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Foreign Minister on Conditions for IAEA Inspections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0806230694 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 2100 GMT 8 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0806230694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [YONHAP report from Kiev] </F>
  [Text] North Korean Foreign Minister Kim Yong-nam said on 
8 June that if the United States agrees to resume the third 
round of DPRK-U.S. talks, North Korea will allow the 
International Atomic Energy Agency to inspect its nuclear 
facilities in Yongbyon. In a news conference after winding up 
his Ukraine visit, Kim Yong-nam said that if the DPRK-U.S. talks 
are resumed, North Korea will guarantee the inspection of the 
nuclear facilities, including the test, measurement, and 
preservation of the fuel rods. 
  Kim Yong-nam also said that the United States is rejecting 
the resumption of the third round of the DPRK-U.S. talks by 
carrying out stalling tactics. He added that since the United 
States and North Korea are the parties directly involved in this 
matter, the only way to resolve this matter is through the 
United States and North. He pointed out that the nuclear issue 
was caused by the United States and that the threat against the 
DPRK stems from the United States. 

</TEXT>

