<H3> <TI>   Defense Ministry Statement Dissociates Army From Politics </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Ministry Statement Dissociates Army From Politics </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS1006141494 Minsk Radio Minsk Network in Belarusian 1200 
GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS1006141494 </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk Radio Minsk Network </F>
<F P=105>  Belarusian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] [Passage omitted] Already at the beginning of the 
election campaign, concern was voiced (?at the session of the 
Collegium of the Defense Ministry) over an increase in political 
and information tension around the Armed Forces. Currently, 
these negative trends are progressing. This caused the Defense 
Ministry to release a statement. 
  The statement says that lately some political structures 
have 
made attempts to speak on behalf of the Armed Forces trying to 
impose their own presidential candidate. Worries are also 
triggered by antiarmy sentiments present in the programs and 
speeches of some presidential candidates. 
  In connection with this, the Defense Ministry states that 
the 
Armed Forces decisively dissociates itself from all attempts 
made by political parties and organizations to involve it in 
battles for power. 
  Another segment from the statement released by the Collegium 
of the Defense Ministry states: Servicemen are full-fledged 
citizens of the Republic. During the elections, they have the 
right to exercise their constitutional right, to express their 
own will, and to vote for any candidate who actually has the 
interests of the state in mind. 

</TEXT>

