<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Army Communique Protests `Misinformation' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Army Communique Protests `Misinformation' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1106202494 Chisinau BASAPRESS in English 2000 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1106202494 </F>
<F P=104>  Chisinau BASAPRESS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tiraspol BASAPRESS, 9/6/1994 -- The 14th Russian 
Army press center made public a declaration stating that "on 4 
June the television station of the Dniester Republic broadcast 
the sensational news that the commander of the 14th Army's 
Tiraspol garrison, Colonel Mikhail Bergman sent a confidential 
letter to Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev. According to 
the television station, which allegedly has a copy of the 
letter, Bergman demanded Grachev's consent in `deposing the 
Dniester Republic's leadership.' The 14th Army command calls the 
`intentional misinformation' broadcast by the television station 
as an attempt to involve the Russian top leadership in the 
current dirty political intrigues. The press center notes that 
they contacted the Russian defense ministry and that no letter 
has been received from Colonel Bergman. The defense ministry 
also said that if such a letter had been received, it would have 
been sent to General Lebed to take 'proper measures against 
instigators.' The 14th Army commander was compelled to send the 
Russian defense ministry the entire text of the letter allegedly 
written by Bergman." "The analysis of the letter shows the 
complicity of certain structures of the self-proclaimed Dniester 
Republic in destabilizing the social-political situation and the 
justification of the extension of the state of emergency," 
states the 14th Army press center. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

