<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Border Checkpoint Talks Begin With Romania </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Border Checkpoint Talks Begin With Romania </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1106205294 Chisinau BASAPRESS in English 2000 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1106205294 </F>
<F P=104>  Chisinau BASAPRESS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chisinau BASAPRESS, 9/6/1994 -- The negotiations 
between the Moldovan and Romanian Ministries of Foreign Affairs 
on changing the status of the [border crossing] points of 
Cahul-Oancea, Sculeni-Sculeni Giurgiulesti, and Costesti-Stanca 
began today in Galati, Romania. The Moldovan delegation, headed 
by Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs Alexandru Burian, is 
comprised by representatives of customs departments. Sources 
from the government told BASAPRESS that these negotiations are 
held according to the 15 February 1994 Governmental Agreement. 
According to it, some passage points would be granted 
international status. The same source mentioned that the, 
Cahul-Oancea, Sculeni-Sculeni Giurgiulesti, and Costesti-Stanca 
passage points were opened in 1991 to facilitate border traffic 
and serve only Moldovan and Romanian citizens and economic 
companies. At the same time, Ukraine and other East European 
countries want to cross their goods and passengers at these 
points, at Giurgiulesti, in particular. The negotiations in 
Galati will not alter the passage regulations for Moldovan and 
Romanian citizens. Economic experts assert that one of the most 
difficult problems arising with this change of the passage 
points' status would be the creation of conditions corresponding 
to European standards for which Moldova is unprepared. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

