<H3> <TI>   Official Denies Police Force To Leave Tighina </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Denies Police Force To Leave Tighina </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1106204894 Chisinau BASAPRESS in English 2000 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1106204894 </F>
<F P=104>  Chisinau BASAPRESS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chisinau BASAPRESS, 9/6/1994 -- Dniester mass media 
announced a possible withdrawal of the Moldovan police from 
Tighina (Bender.) Victor Catana, the co-chairman of the Join 
Control Commission, told BASAPRESS that this is untrue. "Bender 
is an inseparable part of Moldova and thus the city police is a 
constitutional organ," he said. According to the [1992] Snegur- 
Yeltsin agreement, the city is declared a zone of high security 
and, hence, the Moldovan police's presence in Tighina is 
established by the same agreement, said Catana. According to 
him, the local administration subordinated to the 
self-proclaimed Dniester Republic exerts pressure on the police 
and this results in increased crime. "Regardless of these 
actions the police will stay in Bender to perform its duty of 
protecting public order and the rights and interests of the 
people," concluded Catana. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

