<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vice Premier Discusses Agricultural Prospects </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Vice Premier Discusses Agricultural Prospects </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1006154394 Chisinau BASAPRESS in English 0445 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1006154394 </F>
<F P=104>  Chisinau BASAPRESS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chisinau, BASAPRESS, 8/6/1994 -- The land reform is 
not a panacea for the crisis faced by the Moldovan agriculture, 
stated to the newspaper NEZAVISIMAYA MOLDOVA (Independent 
Moldova), Moldovan Vice Premier Valeriu Bulgari. Bulgari called 
the destruction of the current forms of Agricultural enterprises 
technological regression. Without the necessary agricultural 
equipment and infrastructure, small farms will go bankrupt. He 
also mentioned that advanced technologies need huge investments. 
Businessmen from abroad expect that Moldova will achieve a 
political and economic stability and set taxes at the level of 
the European ones or even lower. Moldova has no choice but to 
cooperate with the ex-Soviet republics and Eastern European 
countries. "By founding the Economic Union (EU), I think that 
all problems will be solved on the basis of the equal rights; 
the EU statute is favorable for Moldova." Bulgari added that 
Moldova has chances to reconquer some of its lost positions on 
the Russian market as the excises on goods from the West, which 
made Moldovan wine uncompetitive, will soon go up because 
Russia, as an EU leader, will intensify the measures of 
protecting its market and producers. The protection of the 
internal markets of the EU member states must constitute a 
large-scale strategy, promoted by all members of this community, 
said Bulgari. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

