<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Authorities Concerned Over Future of Baykonur Cosmodrome </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Authorities Concerned Over Future of Baykonur Cosmodrome </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1006142894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1326 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1006142894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Akimov] </F>
  [Text] Alma-Ata [Almaty] 10 June TASS -- The municipal 
council of Leninsk, a satallite town of the Baykonur cosmodrome, 
is concerned over the future of this rocket-launching complex. 
The Kazakh newspaper EKSPRESS-K reports that the council had 
backed the appeal of a group of its members to the Kazakh 
Supreme Soviet, expressing alarmed in connection with the 
absence of a mechanism to implement the Kazakh-Russian agreement 
on the main principles and terms for the use of the cosmodrome. 
  A resolution, adopted in this connection, notes that the 
slowness of the governments of the two countries in implementing 
the achieved agreements places the population of the town in a 
very difficult predicament. The financing of its infrastructure 
was slashed. People were virtually freezing in the production 
premises and in their apartments last winter. The cosmodrome 
facilities could not be used, because this is not allowed during 
very cold periods. 
  The session's resolution was forwarded to corresponding 
committees and commissions of the Kazakh and Russian Parliaments. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

