<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-113 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Akayev Urges Strengthening of State Power </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Akayev Urges Strengthening of State Power </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1306112194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1026 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1306112194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Askar Akayev intends to strengthen state 
power in Kyrgyzstan. He said so at Monday's conference with the 
heads of local government bodies. 
  This does not mean a change in the general political course, 
he explained. According to him, some provisions and concepts 
adopted earlier are untenable and illusory, and the real 
developments in the country's political and economic life make 
it necessary to alter objectives. 
  He continues to be in favor of democracy, Akayev pointed 
out, 
but real life has proved that democratic methods are 
ineffective, that they hinder the endeavors to reach tangible 
results on the road to reforms. 
  Under the circumstances a strong state power has no 
alternative, since "The people are not prepared for 
democracy," Akayev stressed. 
  He will resolutely dismiss those people who will hinder the 
implementation of government resolutions or stand in the way of 
carrying out the program for economic restructuring to be 
accomplished in the next three years. 
  On the other hand, Akayev noted that "we could establish an 
authoritarian regime, as other CIS states did, the more so as 
many want it, but this will be unproductive." 
  The passion for parliamentarianism in Kyrgyzstan has led to 
the fact that the Supreme Council engaged in 
politically-motivated criminal investigations, not in normal 
legislative activity, taking up the duties of the national 
security committee, Interior Ministry and courts of justice, 
which scared the potential investors away. 
  "Many people in Kyrgyzstan viewed parliament as the 
apotheosis of democracy," Akayev stressed. "In the meantime the 
activity of the present legislature hinders the country's 
movement on the road of reforms and creates the reputation of a 
scandalous country for Kyrgyzstan." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

