<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gives Reasons for Slow Economic Progress </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gives Reasons for Slow Economic Progress </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1106154594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1403 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1106154594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On Saturday [11 June] Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev 
said Kyrgyzstan was doomed to remain a long time yet on the 
sidelines of economic progress. Akayev was speaking at a 
conference at the Slavic University, in Bishkek. 
  In Akayev's view, the republic's geopolitical position did 
it 
little credit. Kyrgyzstan was a land-locked Republic and lacked 
other trade communications. Very soon, he said, the republic 
would depend on its neighbors and especially on Russia because 
economically developed nations felt Central Asia as a whole, 
including Kyrgyzstan, lay in a zone of their interests. 
  But, Akayev said, the Republic's industrial potential failed 
to call for serious foreign investment because Kyrgyzstan was 
unable to save its industrial infrastructure. And that was why, 
he said, the government had to discontinue the production of 
many items. 
  According to Akayev, political instability and the absence 
of 
government guarantees impeded foreign investment in the Kyrgyz 
economy. So, he said, Kyrgyzstan would be unlikely to build up 
its international rating in the next 10 to 15 years. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

