<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Calls Russian `Exodus' `Catastrophe' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Calls Russian `Exodus' `Catastrophe' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1206152794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1304 GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1206152794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kirghiz [Kyrgyz] President Askar Akayev said in 
Bishkek that the Russian exodus from Kirghizia [Kyrgyzstan] 
spelt catastrophe for both his republic and Russia, which was 
unable to give roof to many thousands of its sons and daughters. 
  Akayev explained the emigration of ethnic Russians from 
Kirghizia by the imperfection of the local economic reform which 
cause a slump in the living standards and overall 
disillusionment. 
  According to Akayev, 918,000 ethnic Russians lived in 
Kirghizia back in 1990. They accounted for 21.2 percent of the 
Republic's overall population. As of 1 April 1994, though, 
there were some 750,000 ethnic Russians in Kirghizia. They made 
up 17 percent of the overall population. In four years, Akayev 
said, 170,000 Russians had left Kirghizia. That inflicted 
irreparable damages on the Kirghiz economy. 
  Akayev agreed that the social and political problems, for 
example the introduction of Kirghiz as the Republic's official 
language, were largely to blame for the wave of emigration. 
And, Akayev said, Russian-speaking entrepreneurs stood little 
chance in Kirghizia, and discrimination against ethnic Russians 
was, indeed, a fact of everyday life. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

