<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Military: Tension Likely To Mount on Border </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Military: Tension Likely To Mount on Border </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1206153694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1304 GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1206153694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 20 June the Dushanbe government and opposition 
may be expected to resume negotiations in Tehran and that, 
according to the Commander in chief of Russia's border troops 
Andrey Nikolayev, will likely escalate tension on the 
Tajikistan-Afghanistan border. 
  Practice showed, Nikolayev said, that in the runup to, and 
during, the negotiations the opposition would try to do a bit of 
muscle-flexing and put pressure on Dushanbe. In addition, he 
said, the opposition's negotiating team might fail to control, 
in full measure, the opposition's field commanders. A third 
force could instigate fighting and he who paid, Nikolayev said, 
would want an interest on his investment. 
  Nikolayev withheld his view of the possibility of agreement 
between the opposition and those who were holding power in 
Dushanbe. He said, nonetheless, that agreement was possible if 
both sides came to put the people's interests above their own. 
  Nikolayev admitted that Uzbekistan and Kazakhstan failed to 
meet, in full measure, their pledge to protect Tajikistan's 
external border. 

</TEXT>

