<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aliyev Meets Russia's Grachev, Seeks Military Ties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Aliyev Meets Russia's Grachev, Seeks Military Ties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1106131694 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1158 
GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1106131694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Sevindzh Abdullayeva, Mikhail </F>
Shevtsov, and Viktor Shulman] 
  [Text] Baku, 11 Jun -- Talks between the Azerbaijani 
President Geydar Aliyev and Russian Defense Minister Pavel 
Grachev are being held here today with the participation of 
experts on both sides. 
  In a press statement Aliyev stressed the importance of the 
meeting and noted in particular the friendly character of 
relations between the two neighboring states. Of late, he said, 
many steps have been taken to successfully develop and 
strengthen these relations. Nevertheless, a broadening of 
cooperation in Aliyev's view requires closer contacts, including 
closer military contacts. The interests of strengthening the 
security of both Azerbaijan and Russia require this. He took 
the opportunity to ask Pavel Grachev to convey the most cordial 
greetings to Russian President Boris Yeltsin and the Russian 
people on their Independence Day and wished them happiness, 
prosperity, and success on the path of building a democratic 
society. 
  Grachev also advocated the organization of multi-faceted 
cooperation between the two countries and raising it to a higher 
level. In this matter, he stated, Azerbaijan will always meet 
with full understanding on Russia's part. The Russian minister 
said that his trip to Azerbaijan was a familiarization and 
working visit. He expressed confidence that the discussion of 
the planned issues would be successful. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-39866 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov113_r_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-113 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev Comments on Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Grachev Comments on Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1106153294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1345 
GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1106153294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Sevindzh Abdullayeva, Mikhail </F>
Shevtsov and Viktor Shulman] 
  [Text] Baku, 11 Jun -- The Russian Defense Minister Pavel 
Grachev has said that his talks today with Geydar Aliyev, the 
president of Azerbaijan, were "successful." Commenting after 
the meeting on its outcome the head of the Russian defense 
department said that the main attention had been focused on two 
purely military matters. 
  The first matter concerned the future of the Gabala 
[Gabelinskaya] missile attack warning station, a large 
installation in northern Azerbaijan that was previously under 
the control of the armed forces of the former Soviet Union. 
Pavel Grachev said that on this matter he had met with full 
understanding on the part of Azerbaijani President Geydar Aliyev 
that this station is of strategic importance not only for Russia 
and Azerbaijan but also for other CIS countries and the states 
of the whole world. Grachev stated that experts have been given 
the task of studying this matter very quickly so that an 
agreement can be signed on the operation of the installation. 
  The Russian delegation also put forward for consideration by 
the Azerbaijani side a proposal to create a single air defense 
system in the Transcaucasus. This proposal had been discussed 
earlier at talks between Armenia and Georgia, and had been 
accepted by those countries. The head of the Russian defense 
department said that Geydar Aliyev welcomed the idea, and had 
instructed the Azerbaijani defense minister to look into this 
question. Grachev said he hoped for a positive solution. In 
any case, even if Azerbaijan does not give us a positive answer, 
we will build a single air defense system in the Transcaucasus, 
with the participation of Russia, Armenia, and Georgia, -- the 
Russian minister underlined. 
  Speaking of the settlement of the Armenian-Azerbaijani 
conflict, Grachev said that he had learned a lot in a one-to-one 
conversation with Geydar Aliyev. The Russian minister said he 
would brief in detail President Yeltsin on his return to Moscow. 
Grachev said he had learned two important things from this 
conversation. The first one relates to the influence of the 
internal political situation in Azerbaijan on the conflict 
there. The second, according to the minister, is that no narrow 
or departmental agreement on the cease- fire and on stopping the 
military action would have a positive effect until a 
comprehensive political treaty between Russia, Azerbaijan, and 
Armenia on settling this problem has been signed. Such a 
document is now being developed by the Foreign Ministry and 
other departments, he said, speaking of this issue. 
  At present, Azerbaijan and Armenia on the whole are 
observing 
the cease-fire agreement, Grachev said. However, according to 
his information, each of the sides was building up its forces 
and this could lead to a resumption of military actions. At the 
same time, the minister gave assurances that Russia, as 
mediator, was monitoring the situation in the conflict zone. 
  Grachev said that the question of introducing Russian 
peacekeeping forces into the region had not been discussed at 
the meeting. 
  It has become known that the Russian defense minister and 
those accompanying him will return to Moscow this evening. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-39867 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov113_r_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-113 </AU>
