<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Russian Defense Minister's Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Russian Defense Minister's Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Talks With Shevardnadze </H4>

<F P=102> LD1006172794 Tbilisi Radio Tbilisi Network in Georgian 1500 
GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1006172794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi Radio Tbilisi Network </F>
<F P=105>  Georgian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev, who is 
paying a working visit to the Transcaucasus republics, arrived 
from Yerevan in Tbilisi today. [passage omitted] 
  Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev and Eduard 
Shevardnadze, the chairman of the Georgian Supreme Council and 
head of state, held a one-to-one meeting at the Georgian Cabinet 
of Ministers, and were later joined by representatives of the 
Russian and Georgian sides. 
  The meeting discussed issues relating to the settlement of 
the Georgian-Abkhaz conflict, in particular, the timing and 
mechanism for the deployment of CIS peacekeeping forces in the 
conflict zone. The sides also discussed terms and conditions for 
the operation of the Russian military bases on Georgian 
territory. 
  Eduard Shevardnadze said that the meeting could be regarded 
as a new stage in relations between Russia and Georgia. It will 
help implement the plan that envisaged the introduction to the 
conflict area of CIS peacekeeping forces under UN aegis [as 
heard] and the repatriation of refugees and displaced persons. 
  In the second part of the day, the Russian defense minister 
flew to Gudauta to agree the introduction of peacekeeping forces 
to the conflict zone with the Abkhaz side. 
  Before leaving for Gudauta, Pavel Grachev said that the 
military aspect of the deployment of Russian peacekeeping forces 
in Abkhazia had in effect been completely solved. As regards 
the timing of their deployment, that could only be decided at 
political level. 
  The minister said that three motor rifle battalions from the 
Leningrad, Volga, and Urals Military Districts were ready to 
carry out the peace operation as part of a CIS force. Three 
days were needed to transfer them to the conflict zone. Pavel 
Grachev also said that the Gudauta-based 345th Parachute 
Regiment of the Russian Armed Forces might take part in the 
disengagement of forces. In addition to that, said the 
minister, it should not be ruled out that three battalions from 
the Group of Russian Troops in the Transcaucasus might also 
participate in the peace mission in the Georgian-Abkhaz conflict 
zone. The group commander has already been issued with relevant 
instructions. 
  It is expected that the Russian defense minister will return 
to Tbilisi later today to continue the discussion of the details 
of the deployment of CIS peacekeeping forces in Abkhazia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

