<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Russian Defense Minister's Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Russian Defense Minister's Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Government Approves Peacekeepers </H4>

<F P=102> LD1006203794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1940 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1006203794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondents Albert Kochetkov and </F>
Mikhail Shevtsov] 
  [Text] Tbilisi, June 10 (TASS) -- Russian Defense Minister 
Pavel Grachev's mission on the settlement of the 
Georgian-Abkhazian conflict has been a success. After holding 
talks this morning with Georgian leader Eduard Shevardnadze and 
receiving his consent for Russia to begin a peacekeeping 
operation in Abkhazia, the minister left for Gudauta where he 
met with Vladislav Ardzinba and achieved the same result. 
  Taking part in the talks in Gudauta along with the Defense 
Minister Pavel Grachev were Ambassador of the Russian Federation 
to Georgia Vladimir Semskiy and Commander of Airborne Troops of 
the Russian Defense Ministry Colonel-General Gennadiy Podkolzin. 
  A final decision on the beginning of a peacekeeping 
operation 
will depend on the upper house of the Russian parliament. The 
defense minister expressed the hope that a session of the 
federation council scheduled for June 14 would approve Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin's decree on the participation of Russian 
peacekeepers in the settlement of the Georgian-Abkhazian 
conflict. 
  According to the defense minister, a peacekeeping operation 
in Abkhazia will begin three-five days after a political 
decision is adopted. He expressed the hope that along with 
Russia other Commonwealth countries would take part in the 
operation, particularly states - parties to the treaty on 
collective security. 
  In accordance with the worked out plan of the operation in 
Abkhazia, the defense minister explained, the first to start it 
will be units of the 345th Airborne Regiment stationed in 
Gudauta, as well as three battalions from the group of Russian 
troops in Transcaucasian region. The order on their formation 
has been already given. 
  In the future, Pavel Grachev noted, it is planned to bring 
into the zone of disengagement along the Inguri river the main 
forces -- three battalions formed on the basis of peacekeeping 
divisions from the Leningrad and Privolzhskiy military 
districts. The personnel and materiel will be delivered by 
military transport aircraft to airports in Sukhumi and Gudauta. 
  On his return from Gudauta tonight, Pavel Grachev told 
journalists that a final calculation of all aspects of the 
peacekeeping operation and all means and forces to be involved 
in it would be made during this night. It is exactly with this 
aim that from the Tbilisi airport he set for the headquarters of 
the group of Russian troops in the Transcaucasian region where 
all details of the oncoming beginning of the peacekeeping 
operation will be discussed, according to informed sources from 
the government circles in Tbilisi. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

