<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Russian Defense Minister's Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Russian Defense Minister's Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Grachev Departs for Baku </H4>

<F P=102> LD1106093094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0817 
GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1106093094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Albert Kochetkov and Mikhail </F>
Shevtsov] 
  [Text] Tbilisi, 11 Jun -- Russia's Defense Minister Pavel 
Grachev has successfully completed his working visit to Tbilisi. 
He succeeded in obtaining the agreement of the warring Georgian 
and Abkhaz sides on the start in the near future of a 
peacekeeping operation in the conflict zone. 
  Taking part in the festive send-off ceremony were Georgia's 
Prime Minister Otar Patsatsiya, Parliament Speaker Vakhtang 
Goguadze, the command of the Group of Russian Forces in the 
Transcaucasus, Russia's ambassador to Georgia Vladimir Zemskiy, 
and other officials. 
  In the evening prior to his departure Grachev met with his 
Georgian counterpart Lieutenant-General Vardiko Nadibaidze. 
ITAR- TASS correspondents have learned that at this meeting 
questions of the development and strengthening of interaction 
and cooperation between the defense departments of Russia and 
Georgia were discussed, with the conversation being of a 
friendly and constructive nature. 
  Before his departure by plane for Baku early in the morning, 
Grachev met with generals and officers of the staff of the Group 
of Russian Forces in the Transcaucasus. The meeting discussed 
questions of strengthening combat training, social protection 
for personnel and members of their families, options for the 
change-over by Russian troops stationed in Georgia to the 
principle of occupying bases. [perekhod no bazovyy printsip] 
  In Baku, as is expected, Grachev will meet with President 
Geydar Aliyev and will discuss the possibilities for a 
settlement of the Azerbaijani-Armenian conflicts with the 
participation of Russian peacekeeping forces. 

</TEXT>

