<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze on Russia's New Role as Peacemaker </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shevardnadze on Russia's New Role as Peacemaker </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1206062994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0523 
GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1206062994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Albert Kochetkov] </F>
  [Text] Tbilisi, 12 Jun -- "For all friendly states the Day 
of Russia's Independence will be a symbol of the new Russia's 
democratic aspirations," Georgian leader Eduard Shevardnadze, 
the speaker of the Georgian parliament, has told ITAR-TASS. 
  In the opinion of the Georgian leader, Russia is celebrating 
its Independence Day in new and different circumstances. 
Despite the fact that Russia is going through a difficult 
period of establishing itself economically and politically, a 
new social climate is forming in society. 
  "It is vital for all world countries that this country, 
which 
plays the decisive role in whether the post-Soviet region will 
become a conflict-free zone, remains stable," he noted. "If one 
is to speak about Russia's new role in history, it is the 
mission of peacemaker and guarantor of stability." 

</TEXT>

