<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze Issues Edict on Armed Forces Reorganization </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shevardnadze Issues Edict on Armed Forces Reorganization </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1006192094 Tbilisi CONTACT INFORMATION AGENCY in Russian 
0000 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1006192094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi CONTACT INFORMATION AGENCY </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Eduard Shevardnadze, the head of state and commander 
in chief of the Armed Forces, issued an edict introducing a 
number of changes in the organization and structure of the 
Georgian Defense Ministry. 
  The edict says that changes are needed due to the fact that 
the special purpose, rapid reaction and "mobile" units, which 
were set up in the past as part of the country's Armed Forces 
and were mainly staffed with volunteers, are at present having a 
negative effect on the process of creating regular units in the 
Georgian national army. According to the edict, the 
above-mentioned units are to be incorporated into motor rifle 
brigades of the Georgian Armed Forces. 
  The commander in chief's edict abolishes the Military Police 
Directorate on the grounds that it duplicates the duties of the 
republic's law enforcement bodies and fails to meet modern 
requirements. 
  The head of state's edict declares disbanded all military 
formations and groups that are not part of the Armed Forces. It 
says that their personnel and weaponry are to be used to staff 
and equip motor rifle brigades. 
  With the aim of establishing strict military discipline and 
order at Defense Ministry units, the edict orders the setting up 
of commandant's offices and garrisons in all towns and 
settlements where such units are based. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

