<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Proposals for Steps Under NATO Plan Delivered </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Proposals for Steps Under NATO Plan Delivered </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS1306094694 Tallinn BNS in English 1617 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1306094694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, June 11, BNS -- Lithuanian Foreign 
Minister Povilas Gylys at a meeting with NATO Assistant 
Secretary General Sergio Balanzino in Istanbul Friday delivered 
Lithuania's set of propositions for activity under the NATO 
Partnership for Peace program, the Foreign Ministry press office 
said. 
  Gylys takes part in Istanbul in a foreign ministers meeting 
of the North Atlantic Cooperation Council [NACC]. 
  The document delivered to the NATO assistant secretary 
general lays the basis for outlining a separate cooperation 
program between Lithuania and NATO under the partnership plan. 
  The Lithuanian foreign minister is his speech before the 
NACC 
meeting pronounced his country's wish that the NATO partnership 
program would take into account the needs of each participating 
country. In his words the Partnership for Peace program allows 
active partners to play a great role in expanding the alliance. 
  Gylys also referred in his speech to the problem of Russian 
military transits to the Kaliningrad enclave through Lithuania's 
territory. He underscored that finding a solution to the issue 
must not be linked to carrying out the stipulations of the 
Lithuanian- Russian agreements that have been signed earlier. 

</TEXT>

