<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Factions Issue Statement on Korean Peninsula Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Duma Factions Issue Statement on Korean Peninsula Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1006123794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1206 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1006123794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Ivan Novikov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 10 TASS -- Duma factions of communists, 
agrarians and liberal democrats lead by Vladimir Zhirinovskiy 
took a joint stand once again. They issued a joint statement 
"on the situation in the Korean peninsula" which was circulated 
in the lower house of parliament on Friday. 
  These factons noted a sharp aggravation of the situation on 
the Korean peninsula, close to Russian borders. Deputies 
pointed out that "certain circles in the United States want to 
compel the DPRK to accept humiliating terms of the settlement of 
the so-called nuclear problem". In this connection 
representatives of the three above-mentioned Duma factions 
expressed "perplexity" at the statement of the Russian 
leadership which, in the opinion of deputies, "actually sided 
with one party in the conflict, South Korea". 
  The deputies expressed disapproval of Russia's decision to 
join in the economic sanction against the DPRK. "Our national 
interests would be suited by giving up power methods, creating 
conditions for a dialogue between the north and south of Korea 
and implementing the concept of a non-nuclear zone in the Korean 
peninsula", the statement says. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

