<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Addresses Council on NATO Partnership, Peacekeeping </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev Addresses Council on NATO Partnership, Peacekeeping </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1006141494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1355 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1006141494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Dmitriy Gorokhov and Sergey </F>
Feoktistov] 
  [Text] Istanbul June 10 TASS -- Russian Foreign Minister 
Andrey Kozyrev has called on the international community to help 
Russia in its peace-making on territory of the former Soviet 
Union by sending observers and rendering material support at the 
current session of the North Atlantic Cooperation Council. In 
his words, Russia is carrying an increasing peace-making burden 
in former Soviet republics. 
  Closer interaction of the council with European neutral 
states, which are experienced in peace-making, would help to 
increase the collective peace-making potential, said the 
minister. 
  Kozyrev urged the need for closer cooperation of CSCE and 
the 
council in peace-keeping operations as it is envisaged by the 
council's plan for 1994, and suggested to form a corresponding 
joint working group. 
  The Russian concept of European partnership provides for 
coordination of military, political and peace-making interaction 
by the North Atlantic Cooperation Council and the leading role 
of CSCE, Kozyrev told the council's session. In his opinion, 
the council can and must gradually transform into an independent 
body to be based on equality of all participants and not on the 
scheme of "NATO plus partners". 
  Kozyrev called for the involvement of a large number of CSCE 
members in the council activities, permanent contacts between 
the two organizations and the use of the council's abilities in 
the implementation of the Partnership for Peace program. 
  Russia is striving for deepened partnership with NATO 
without 
mutual vetoes and "surprises", Kozyrev told the council. "The 
Partnership for Peace program is starting. We plan to come to 
Brussels to boost a program of deepened cooperation between 
Russia and NATO, including a framework document, as soon as the 
NATO headquarters finalize the preparations," said Kozyrev. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

