<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev on Joining Partnership, Naples Summit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev on Joining Partnership, Naples Summit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1006224194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 2137 
GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1006224194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Dmitriy Gorokhov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 11 June -- Russia would like to come to an 
agreement with NATO on forms of partnership before the meeting 
between President Boris Yeltsin and the leaders of the seven 
leading Western states, which is to be held in Naples next 
month. Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev said this on 
Friday [10 June] evening. 
  Speaking to journalists on board his plane to Moscow from 
Istanbul, where he had attended a session of the North Atlantic 
Cooperation Council, Kozyrev called on the parties "to finish 
their ideological disputes more quickly and get down to 
business." He had noted sympathy in this regard in his talks 
with U.S. State Secretary Warren Christopher, among others. 
  As President Boris Yeltsin said on Friday, Kozyrev noted, we 
are talking about the signing of a framework document and of the 
NATO- Russia program. Incidentally, the minister added, in the 
communique following the NATO council session, which has just 
taken place, Russia's viewpoint is taken into account. It talks 
about a program that will reflect the Russian Federation's 
specific role and weight. 
  Russia will sign both the framework agreement and a 
substantive and much more thorough program for partnership as 
soon as the documents setting down the relevant agreements are 
ready. This should be done quickly, before the meeting in 
Naples, the minister said. 
  The minister was asked whether it was probable that the 
agreement between Russia and the European Union would be signed 
at the forthcoming meeting of European Union leaders on the 
island of Kerkira (Corfu), in which it is expected Boris Yeltsin 
may take part. "I think that this probability is constantly 
growing," Kozyrev stated. "The remaining matters are technical 
ones connected with the translation of the text of the accords 
into the languages of the countries involved in the agreement." 
According to the head of Russia's diplomacy the possibility of 
completing the necessary preparatory work in a short space of 
time was confirmed too during his conversation in Istanbul with 
Karolos Papoulias, the foreign minister of Greece, which is the 
current chairman of the European Union. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

