<F P=102>   LD1006181994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1629 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1006181994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow is warning that if the law on citizenship, 
which Latvia's parliament adopted Thursday at its second 
reading, comes into effect, "this may seriously complicate 
relations between Russia and Latvia," and Prime Minister Viktor 
Chernomyrdin may have to postpone his visit to Riga, Russian 
Deputy Foreign Minister Vitaliy Churkin told Interfax Friday. 
  Churkin said he hoped that the law on citizenship will not 
have an impact on the implementation of the agreements on troop 
withdrawal, on the situation of retired Russian servicemen and 
on the issue of the radar station in Skrunda signed by the two 
countries' presidents in Moscow. He said these agreements were 
too important to be affected even by such a serious document as 
the law on citizenship. 

