<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow To Continue Mediation in Dniester Settlement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moscow To Continue Mediation in Dniester Settlement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1006191694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1807 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1006191694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Boris Krivoshey] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 10 TASS -- Russia will continue active 
mediation in settlement of the trans-Dniester conflict, 
plenipotentiary representative of the Russian president 
Vladillen Vasev told ITAR-TASS today upon the completion of his 
Moldovan trip. 
  Slightly more than a month has passed since the signing of a 
joint statement by Moldovan and trans-Dniester leaders, he said. 
This period can be described as organizational. Working groups 
have been set up to focus on financial, economic relations and 
political settlement, which is the future state-legal status of 
the trans- Dniester region. 
  "Economic issues are natural and there are people who are 
tackling these problems. I think it will be easy for them to 
pull their efforts and elaborate corresponding agreements. They 
have already started to do it," said Vasev. 
  In his opinion, the issue of financial-economic relations 
remains difficult. It is a certain stumbling stone in 
Moldovan-trans- Dniester relations. "But I think the sides will 
solve this problem," he added. 
  The most difficult problem is still the state-legal status 
of 
the trans-Dniester region. The problem is in the focus of the 
sides' leaders and heads of expert groups - First Deputy 
Moldovan Foreign Minister Nikolae Osmokescu and trans-Dniester 
State Secretary Valeriy Litskay. 
  On the whole, the current stage of negotiations can be 
described as preparatory. "Despite certain differences and 
rather heated debates, one can say that the general stand of the 
sides has become more constructive, they intend to reach 
compromises and certain results have been achieved. The 
preparatory period is necessary to reach agreements. The sides 
have fixed no time for them, but it would be better not to drag 
out this period," said Vasev. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

