<F P=102>   LD1006134294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1324 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1006134294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Nikolay Kondratenko] </F>
  [Text] St. Petersburg June 10 TASS -- Finnish Prime 
Minister Esko Aho arrived in St. Petersburg on Friday to attend 
the ceremony of the opening of the third plenary session of the 
Commission for International Assistance to St. Petersburg and 
the Leningrad region to attract investments and develop business. 
  Among members of the commission headed by Doctor Henry 
Kissinger and St. Petersburg Mayor Anatoliy Sobchak are 
representatives of state, governmental, business and acamedic 
circles of Great Britain, Russia, the United States, France, 
Finland and Sweden. 
  Participants in the plenary session will discuss new 
projects 
aimed at developing banks, agrarian business and the 
reconstruction of the St. Petersburg maritime port. 
  At the ceremony at the hotel "Astoria" the Finnish prime 
minister will address participants in the session and hold talks 
with chairman of the St. Petersburg government, Mayor Anatoliy 
Sobchak. Late in the evening he will leave for Finland. 

