<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Federation Council To Discuss Georgian-Abkhaz Conflict </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Federation Council To Discuss Georgian-Abkhaz Conflict </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1006161394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1437 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1006161394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: Compiled by </F>
Nikolay Zherebtsov, Andrey Petrovskiy; edited by Vladimir 
Shishlin] 
  [Text] On Thursday President Boris Yeltsin signed a decree 
"On Participation of the Russian Federation in the Peacekeeping 
Operation in the Zone of the Georgian-Abkhazian Conflict". 
  As reports the presidential press service, issuance of this 
decree was caused by aggravation of the situation in the 
conflict zone, support of this peacekeeping operation on the 
part of CIS countries, and the request on the part of Georgian 
and Abkhazian leaders to urgently deploy peacekeeping forces in 
the conflict zone. 
  Yeltsin commissioned the government to ensure formation of 
an 
appropriate military contingent on the basis of the Russian 
units which have the status of peacekeeping forces by using the 
infrastructure of the Group of the Russian Forces in 
Transcaucases. The Russian contingent can be later on 
strengthened on the decision of the Federation Council of the RF 
Federal Assembly. 
  The decree is to go into effect since the moment of its 
signing, however, in accordance with the RF Constitution the 
Federation Council is to determine the time of the operation. 
The next sitting of the upper chamber has been scheduled for 
June 21, however, Vladimir Shumeyko, chairman of the chamber, 
does not rule out that he would convene an extraordinary sitting 
to consider this issue. IF Note: The previous week the upper 
chamber of the Russian parliament declined Boris Yeltsin's 
request to approve introduction of Russian peacekeeping forces 
into the zone of the Georgian-Abkhazian conflict (with a 
majority of only one vote). 
  Meanwhile, on Thursday Russian Defense Minister Pavel 
Grachev 
reported to Interfax in Yerevan that everything is ready for the 
introduction of peacekeeping forces into the zone of the 
Georgian-Abkhazian conflict, "however, decision of politicians 
is needed to start the operation." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

