<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Adopts Draft Oil, Gas Law </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Duma Adopts Draft Oil, Gas Law </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1006191494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1629 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1006191494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia's State Duma (lower chamber of parliament) 
has adopted the draft law on oil and gas (by one vote 
difference), removing from it a provision on the exclusive right 
of the central authorities to "dictate the terms" for 
prospecting, exploration and the actual production of oil and 
gas, their transportation and storage. 
  Interfax was informed by the Russian Fuel and Energy 
Ministry 
that some of the department's functions would now be transferred 
to local authorities. 
  Fuel and Energy Minister Yuriy Shafranik told Interfax that 
the removal of those articles from the draft had been another 
necessary compromise. He said that during a year and a half of 
revision, much had been lost from its content in the search for 
compromises. 
  However, he said he was happy that the draft law had been 
adopted at its first reading. Without such a document, he said, 
the government would find it very difficult to exercise control 
over the holders of licenses for oil and gas production. 
  The president, government and constituent members of the 
Russian Federation, parliamentary committees and fractions must, 
by 24 June, submit their comments to prepare for the draft law's 
second reading before 1 July. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

