<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Groznyy Denies Dudayev Undermined Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Groznyy Denies Dudayev Undermined Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1206162194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1515 
GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1206162194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Groznyy, 12 June (CHECHENPRESS-TASS) -- The Chechen 
Ministry of Foreign Affairs has refuted accusations that 
president Dzhokhar Dudayev was responsible for the collapse of 
the talks with Russia. In a statement issued today by 
CHECHENPRESS, the Foreign Ministry of Chechnya says that 
"Groznyy has never received any proposals or documents from the 
Russian leadership for the forthcoming talks," and therefore the 
Chechen leadership "strongly refutes the accusations that it has 
undermined the allegedly planned talks." The document also 
states that "the Chechen Republic is willing to start talks with 
the Russian Federation only on the principles of equality, with 
no preconditions, and only if Russia abandons the policy of 
state terrorism." 
  The CHECHENPRESS report says that the Chechen Foreign 
Ministry has been provoked to issue the statement because 
"Russian mass media has published reports in which officials 
from the administration of the Russian President and from the 
Ministry for Nationalities and Regional Policy are blaming 
Dzhokhar Dudayev, president of Chechnya, for the collapse of the 
allegedly planned talks between the Chechen Republic and the 
Russian Federation." 

</TEXT>

