<H3> <TI>   Ossetian Leader Calls for High-Level Peace Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ossetian Leader Calls for High-Level Peace Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1006162594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1446 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1006162594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Shanayev] </F>
  [Text] Vladikavkaz June 10 TASS -- On his return from 
Moscow, Akhsarbek Galazov, president of the Republic of North 
Ossetia, informed today members of the Presidium of the 
government of the republic of his meeting with Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin in Moscow on June 9. 
  According to Akhsarbek Galazov, "the meeting was fruitful. I 
told the Russian president about the situation in the zone under 
the state of emergency regime, and the concrete steps being made 
by the leadership of North Ossetia on the settlement of the 
situation in the zone of the Ossetian-Ingush conflict. The road 
to peace and accord in the region lies only through 
negotiations, and these goals cannot be achieved by forcible 
methods." 
  North Ossetian leaders also discussed issues connected with 
the celebration of the 220th anniversary of Ossetia joining 
Russia and the 210th anniversary of the foundation of the city 
of Vladikavkaz. 
  The president of North Ossetia proposed within the framework 
of these celebrations to organize in Vladikavkaz a meeting of 
all leaders of the Caucasian region with the participation of 
the president of the Russian Federation and the head of the 
Russian government during which it would be possible to consider 
socio-political, economic and inter-ethnic problems, as well as 
the roads to peace and accord in the region. 
  During his talks with President Boris Yeltsin, Akhsarbek 
Galazov stressed, the two sides also touched on the problem of 
signing a full-scale treaty between the Russian Federation and 
the Republic of North Ossetia. This would give the possibility 
to settle social and economic problems of North Ossetia more 
purposively. 

</TEXT>

