Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zlenko Accepts North Atlantic Council's Crimea Stand </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zlenko Accepts North Atlantic Council's Crimea Stand </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1206123994 Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service in Ukrainian 
0700 GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1206123994 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] For a state like Ukraine, participation in the 
sitting of the North Atlantic Cooperation Council promotes its 
gradual integration into the processes and structures now 
emerging in Europe. Ukraine's Foreign Minister Zlenko declared 
this in an interview for Ukrainian journalists after the Council 
had ended its sitting in Istanbul. Zlenko believes that such 
gatherings facilitate an immediate and open dialogue with 
partners, offering the chance to explain a position more 
clearly, while at the same time allowing the state to win 
supporters on an array of urgent issues. 
  Zlenko emphasized that this year's conference of heads of 
foreign political departments from 38 countries was, to a 
certain extent, a success with regard to greater understanding 
of existing problems and defining approaches to solutions. 
Zlenko expressed satisfaction with the fact that the statement 
adopted at the sitting of the North Atlantic Cooperation 
Council, which assesses the situation around Crimea, notes that 
the Crimean issue should be solved in compliance with the UN 
Charter and the Final Act of the Conference on Security and 
Cooperation in Europe and with respect to Ukraine's territorial 
integrity. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-39953 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov113_e_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-113 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian-Ukrainian Border Area Leaders Discuss Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian-Ukrainian Border Area Leaders Discuss Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS1006134894 Donetsk DONBASS in Russian 1 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> WS1006134894 </F>
<F P=104>  Donetsk DONBASS </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Stanislav Tyshchenko: "Border Oblasts"] </F>
  [Text] Although the border between Ukraine and the Russian 
Federation exists de jure and de facto, it somehow defies 
comprehension. It is too bizarre a fact, especially for elderly 
people. This is why it will not be taken seriously yet for a 
long time. But still, this is a fact. The division of the two 
sovereign states has been made and cannot be undone. It dealt a 
hard blow primarily to the economy of the former Soviet Union. 
Enterprises tightly linked with each other started to lose 
their ground. The absence of a single center with its almighty 
State Planning Committee, the disruption of links to the quick, 
and chaos in settlements of accounts led to the present 
condition. What next? 
  In eastern Ukraine, southern Russia, and the border-adjacent 
regions, attempts are being undertaken to somehow resuscitate 
economic relations based on the current situation in both 
countries. The press has already reported that border area 
leaders met in Belgorod and Kharkov to lay the groundwork for 
closer financial and economic cooperation. A similar meeting 
took place last week in Donetsk. It was held behind closed 
doors, and at a press conference held on 27 May, its 
participants were not too talkative, asking the journalists for 
questions without making any introduction. This is only natural 
-- everything is still in a "suspended condition" of 
preparations, initial work, etc. Besides, an unclear political 
situation at either side of the border offers no strong grounds 
to hope for success of the planned undertaking. 
  However, there is a movement forward. A council of border 
area leaders was organized, and an agreement is in the works 
between Ukrainian and Russian Governments on cooperation among 
border areas. The status of those oblasts and specific routing 
of capital circulation is being determined. 
  The gist of the responses from the press conference 
participants is that the main purpose of this unconventional 
bilateral body is to reduce, if not eliminate, border and 
customs barriers and to make cooperation on the border more 
profitable, efficient, and to improve the living standards of 
Russian and Ukrainian people. 
  Of course, the intentions are good. But will they become a 
reality? This will depend on decisions made on the government 
level. Incidentally, the meeting was attended by 
representatives of Russian and Ukrainian presidents and 
governments. The following oblasts were represented: Donetsk, 
Lugansk, Sumy, and Kharkov (the delegation from Chernigov Oblast 
did not arrive). The Russian side was represented by Belgorod, 
Bryansk, Voronezh, Rostov, and Kursk Oblasts. 
  At the press conference, it was particularly stressed that 
the entire work of the border oblast leaders' council is 
intended to solve purely economic and humanitarian issues, but 
not political ones. For example, the association for economic 
cooperation "Russian-Ukrainian Union" is being established. 
Work is being conducted on the implementation of Leonid 
Kravchuk's edict on free education for Ukrainian and Russian 
students at colleges and universities located in the border 
areas. 
  In other words, the process has gotten off to a good start. 
The most important thing is that it is peaceful, based on 
mutual understanding, and that it pursues good intentions. 
  The next meeting, or to be more precise, the meeting of the 
council, is scheduled for September in Rostov-on-Don. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-39954 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov113_e_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-113 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radetskyy on Upcoming U.S. Visit, Russian Navy Base </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Radetskyy on Upcoming U.S. Visit, Russian Navy Base </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1006220994 Kiev UT-1 Television Network in Ukrainian 1800 
GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1006220994 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UT-1 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On the eve of his official visit to the United 
States of America, which begins on 13 June, Ukrainian Army 
General Vitaliy Radetskyy, Ukraine's minister of defense, met 
representatives of the U.S. mass media accredited in Kiev. 
  Vitaliy Radetskyy related that he would be meeting the U.S. 
vice president, the secretary of defense, well-known senators, 
and the Ukrainian diaspora. Ukraine's minister of defense will 
also visit a number of military bases and observe the process of 
destroying a strategic ballistic missile and its launching silo. 
Among the issues it is planned to discuss during the week-long 
visit the problems of the development of Ukraine's armed forces, 
the continuation of nuclear disarmament in accordance with the 
trilateral statement by the presidents of the United States, 
Ukraine and Russia, national security, Ukraine's participation 
in the Partnership for Peace program, the problem of Crimea and 
the division of the Black Sea Fleet occupy an important place. 
  When the U.S. journalists asked where, in the opinion of the 
Ukrainian military minister, Ukraine's Navy should be based, 
Vitaliy Radetskyy replied: 
  [Begin Radetskyy recording] There is no talk about this 
because [words indistinct] the Crimea is a constituent part of 
Ukraine. This issue is not even being raised, and it should not 
be raised either. Only one issue is being raised -- the site 
for the temporary basing for the Russian Navy. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-39955 </DOCNO>
