<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Briefing Lists States Supporting Country's Stance on Crimea </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Briefing Lists States Supporting Country's Stance on Crimea </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1006162794 Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY in Ukrainian 9 Jun 94 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> AU1006162794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Solidarity as Political Support"] </F>
  [Text] External political departments of Argentina, 
Denmark, Israel, China, and Japan have recently made official 
statements in support of Ukraine with regard to resolving the 
conflict situation in the Crimea. This became known at a 
briefing at Ukraine's Ministry of Foreign Affairs. In addition 
to official circles of the world's leading countries, 
international organizations, public associations, and the 
Ukrainian diaspora have also demonstrated their solidarity with 
our state. All of them are in favor of a peaceful settlement of 
the conflict situation in which the principles set by the CSCE 
-- inviolability of borders and maintenance of states' 
territorial integrity -- will be adhered to. It was also stated 
at the briefing that a Ukrainian delegation headed by minister 
of foreign affairs A. Zlenko will soon visit Istanbul where it 
will take part in the session of the Council of the North 
Atlantic Cooperation. The program "Partnership for Peace" will 
be the main topic of the discussion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

