<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Islamic Democratic Party Changes Name, Nominates Candidate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Islamic Democratic Party Changes Name, Nominates Candidate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1206152394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1443 GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1206152394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Islamic Democratic Party of Russia nominated for 
presidency at the upcoming elections in 1996 of its leader, 
Khadzhi Akhmadiyev. 
  At the congress of the Islamic Party in Moscow, where less 
than a dozen of representatives of the Moscow and Saratov party 
organizations took part, it was decided to change the name of 
the organization for a [as received] Moslem Civilized Party. 
Its leader Akhmadiyev received the right to appoint personnally 
people for senior posts of the party. 
  Akhmadiyev has told Interfax, the party has about five 
thousand members, mainly in places where Tatars live, and 
considers its potential partners all organization of the 
democratic spectrum. He said that even if financial aid is 
offered from abroad, for example from Iran, Iraq or Saudi 
Arabia, we shall not reject it to be able to take independent 
decisions without any pressure from the outside, said Akhmadiyev. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

